<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Calls for Balance Development in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Burundi Tuesday called
for balance development across the world in the process of
globalization, and more official development assistance to boost
the growth of African fragile economies.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to general debate of the 53rd General Assembly
session, which entered the second day Tuesday, President Pierre
Buyoya of Burundi said, "At this time of globalization, sustained
efforts must be made by the international community to promote
balance development in all parts of the world."
</P>
<P>
Most of African countries, together with other underdeveloped
nations, are being marginalized by the process of globalization,
which took shape on the basis of the development of regional
trade, the flow of information and technological advancement.
</P>
<P>
"Africa deserves special attention," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If development through trade is being activated, then the
official development assistance must be increased in order to
encourage the growth of our economies which are still fragile," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is being crushed under the weight of debt, it must be
eased and done away with the poor countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the sanctions imposed on his country in July 1996, the
president said, "In fact, the impact of embargo on the people of
Burundi is devastating." For example, school attendance has
dropped from 70 percent to 43 percent in the east African country
following the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, a land-locked country, is suffering from the
sanctions, and "the situation of Burundi is no worse than any
other country in the Great Lakes region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Burundi "needs international solidarity, and
humanitarian assistance must be increased to help our people
affected by the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions are the main obstacles on the way towards lasting
peace in Burundi, the president said, while calling for
international cooperation with his country without any further
delay.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Burundi is resolved to do its utmost to
ensure the success of the peace process" in the country, he said,
adding that his government is advocating solution of the crisis
through political dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
