<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister Leaves for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee left here Tuesday evening for New York to attend
the 53rd session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
During his stay there, Vajpayee is scheduled to meet his
Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif Wednesday for talks on the
disputes between the two countries, including the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee will deliver a speech at the U.N. General Assembly on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said India is likely to come under intense
pressure from the world body during its current session over its
nuclear tests conducted in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The world community has strongly condemned the nuclear tests by
India and Pakistan, and urged them to stop nuclear weapons
development programs and sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT). The United States, which has imposed economic sanctions
against India and Pakistan following their nuclear tests,
initiated negotiations on the CTBT with the two countries in June,
yet there has been no tangible result yet.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said last Wednesday that India was not prepared to
sign the CTBT in its present form, saying his government was
seeking a different arrangement, especially with regard to
transfer of high technology and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
At his scheduled lunch together with Sharif in New York on
Wednesday, Vajpayee will discuss modalities with him for
resumption of bilateral dialogue on all outstanding issues between
their two countries, including Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
