<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Small Parties, Big Roles in German Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Under Germany's proportional
representation voting system, a party needs to score at least five
percent of the votes in order to win any seats in the federal
parliament, a hurdle designed to promote political consensus and
prevent weak governments.
</P>
<P>
According to opinion polls, all of the small German parties are
hovering at the dangerous point: the Greens at six or seven
points, the FDP at around five percent and the PDS at about four.
</P>
<P>
The FDP, the traditional kingmaker in German politics, has been
in every German government for nearly 30 years, first in alliance
with the SPD and then with Kohl's conservatives since 1982.
</P>
<P>
But the party known for its pro-free-market policies has seen
its public support dip sharply in the past decade and has been
kept out 12 of the country's 16 state parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, however, say that he will only rule with the FDP, no
other small parties.
</P>
<P>
The Greens, founded in 1980 and replaced the FDP as the third
strongest party in Germany in 1994, are hoping to come to power
this time in alliance with the SPD.
</P>
<P>
But they have also lost support heavily since earlier this year
after making a series of radical demands, including a call to
triple gasoline prices over a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that a possible SPD-Greens coalition would
largely depend on the fate of the PDS.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing party, which is supported mainly by East Germans,
got 30 seats in the German parliament in the 1994 vote by winning
three voting districts outright, an alternative condition to get
into parliament if a party falls short of the five-percent hurdle.
</P>
<P>
The PDS has said it wants to enter the federal parliament again
by winning four direct mandates this time.
</P>
<P>
If it failed, the SPD and the Greens might be able to muster
the majority to govern. But if the party made it, a SPD-Greens
government would have to count on the support from the PDS, a
possibility that has been ruled out by Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, it has been widely speculated
the two largest parties, the CDU and the SPD, might be forced to
form a so-called "grand coalition" between themselves, something
Germany has not seen since 1969.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls show such a "grand coalition" is increasingly
popular with the German voters who want some political change
after 16 years of Kohl but meanwhile fear too much risks.
</P>
<P>
The SPD candidate Schroeder has not ruled out leading such a
grand coalition government but Kohl has said he does want to do
that.
</P>
<P>
In such an event, Kohl has noted that he would rather step down
and make the way for his anointed successor and CDU parliamentary
leader Wolfgang Schaeuble. More

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
