<HEADLINE> Annan Appeals for Support to UNMIBH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday appealed to the Security Council members to
fully support the United Nations Mission in Bosnia and Herzegovina
(UNMIBH) in its efforts to create multi-ethnic police services in
the country.
</P>
<P>
In a new report on the UNMIBH, Annan also emphasized that the
strong and consistent support of the NATO Stabilization Force
(SFOR) will continue to be critically important in providing
adequate security arrangements for the successful implementation
of the UNMIBH's mandate.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general described the progress in police
restructuring in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, but
added that in Republika Srpska, "there has been less progress."
</P>
<P>
Annan noted that the UNMIBH's mandate of police restructuring
had grown to include independent investigation into human rights
abuses by the local police and the identification of impediments
to achieving a depoliticized judiciary capable of delivering
impartial and neutral justice.
</P>
<P>
"The quick recruitment of highly qualified legal experts for
the Judicial System Assessment Program was a positive development
worth noting," the U.N. chief added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
