<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Clinton Job Approval Holds Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Opinion polls conducted
after U.S. television showed President Bill Clinton's grand jury
testimony in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal showed Tuesday that
the airing was less damaging than his critics had predicted.
</P>
<P>
A Gallup poll conducted for CNN and USA Today showed that 66
percent of respondents still approved of the job Clinton is doing,
six points higher than the figure Sunday, the day before the
broadcast. The approval figure on the previous Sunday was 64
percent.
</P>
<P>
The same percentage rejected impeachment, but 39 percent
thought Clinton should resign, the poll showed. USA Today said 81
percent of respondents believed Clinton definitely or probably
lied under oath to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
In an NBC News poll, only 28 percent of respondents believed
the president was telling the truth but 57 percent did not believe
the president should resign.
</P>
<P>
An ABC News poll showed that 70 percent believed Clinton was
right to refuse to talk about the sexual details of his
relationship with Lewinsky and 59 percent thought prosecutors were
wrong to ask detailed, probing, explicit questions.
</P>
<P>
The ABC poll showed Clinton's job approval holding steady at
around 60 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Small Parties, Big Roles in German Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- With opinion polls show that
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's party is closing the gap with the
rival Social Democrats (SPD), the small German parties have become
critical in deciding the outcome of the country's upcoming general
elections.
</P>
<P>
With the national vote just five days away, German polls put
the support rates for Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
party and the main opposition SPD both at about 40 percentage
points, with the CDU trailing the latter by only two to three
points, far less than the 12 points registered in April this year.
</P>
<P>
It was the closest election race in Germany's post-war era,
German pollsters said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, 68, has been leading a center-right ruling coalition --
consisting of the CDU, its Bavarian sister party, the Christian
Social Union (CSU), and the junior coalition partner, the Free
Democratic Party (FDP) -- uninterruptedly since 1982.
</P>
<P>
He is already the longest-serving German chancellor since 1945
and Europe's most durable statesman.
</P>
<P>
Pinning his hope on a large number of undecided voters, Kohl
has stressed that he has good chance to make it again this time.
</P>
<P>
A serious challenge, however, comes from Gerhard Schroeder, the
54-year-old SPD chancellor candidate and a political fresh face,
who many analysts say represents a broad public desire for change
after 16 years of rule by Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Riding on a public outcry about the near-record high
unemployment and a reform standstill in Germany, Schroeder, who
pledges to adopt policies to combine modernity with social justice
in Germany, is leading Kohl all the way since last year in opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
However, as the election draws near, it seems more likely that
neither Kohl nor Schroeder would win absolute majority in order to
govern alone, thus making it necessary for a ruling coalition with
the smaller parties as was the case in most of Germany's post-war
history.
</P>
<P>
The future lineup of the German government will hinge on
whether the smaller parties, such as the ecologist Greens, the
pro-business FDP, and the Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS)
which grew out of the former East German Communist Party, would
get into parliament, German commentators said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
