<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Decrees Russian Government Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin signed on Tuesday a presidential decree on "the Structure
of the Federal Executive Agencies."
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, said an Interfax news agency report, the
Russian prime minister, as the head of government, would have six
deputies, including two first deputies.
</P>
<P>
The decree calls for the formation of five new ministries --
the Ministry for Anti-Monopoly Policy and Support for
Entrepreneurial Activities, the Ministry for Regional Policy, the
Ministry for Nationality Policy, the Ministry for Affairs of the
Commonwealth of Independent States and the Ministry of Trade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Anti-Monopoly Committee, the State
Committee for Support and Development of Small Entrepreneurial
Activities, the Federal Service on Regulating Natural Monopolies
on Transport, the Ministry for Regional and Nationality Policy
would be abolished.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has accepted a proposal by Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov to involve Central Bank Chairman Viktor Geraschenko and
President of the Russian Academy of Sciences Yuri Osipov in the
government work on par with the members of the government
presidium.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, the State Land Committee, the State
Committee for Youth Affairs, the State Committee of Fisheries, the
State Committee of Building Architectural and Housing Policy, the
State Committee of Standards and Metrology are to be created.
</P>
<P>
Two new Federal Services -- the Federal Service of Geodesy and
Cartography and the Federal Service for Hydrometeorology and
Environmental Monitoring would to be established.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin appointed Primakov as prime minister on September 11
after sacking Sergei Kiriyenko's government on August 23. The
president by far has appointed two first deputy prime ministers,
three deputy prime ministers and some key government ministers.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the new government will be concluded within
this week, media reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
