<HEADLINE> Iran Sees No Real Change in U.S. Attitude Towards Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami said Tuesday that there was no real changes in
the behavior or attitude of the United States towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that despite U.S. President Bill Clinton's more
respectful tone towards Islam, Iran had not seen real changes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference with Western reporters, Khatami
listed a series of negative actions by the United States,
including economic sanctions and efforts to prevent oil and gas
pipelines crossing Iran.
</P>
<P>
"These examples and others show that in behavior and in
attitude there has been no real changes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president renewed his call for dialogue between the Iranian
and American people, including scholars, cultural figures and
leaders of civil society, to remove misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed that political government-to-government
relations depended on actions, not just words.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also called for a change in U.S. policy to press Israel
into giving more territory and rights to Palestinians. 
</P>
