<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Not to Suspend Loans to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank said here
Monday it would not suspend its loans to Albania in the wake of
recent violent turmoil in the country.
</P>
<P>
Karlos Elbirt, head of the World Bank's office in Tirana, said
his office is fully operational as the bank continues its funding
for various projects in this Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
Elbirt hoped that the 27 ongoing projects, with a total of 350
million U.S. dollars pledged by the Washington-based official
bank, would be accomplished as initially scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 200 million dollars have been executed to finance
projects in the transportation, road construction, education,
electricity, environmental protection and agriculture sectors.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were to address the fear that the international
financial institution might suspend its loans in light of the tiny
country's political turbulence starting about 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations and subsequent riots were triggered by the
September 10 murder of Azem Hajdari, a leading opposition deputy
at the parliament and a co-founder of the Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Economic Growth Slows Down in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
registered a real-term gross domestic product (GDP) growth of 0.2
percent in the year's second quarter, Eurostat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, said the Luxembourg-based official statistical
bureau of the EU, the 15-nation regional bloc realized a 0.6
percent GDP expansion in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
April through June, Denmark led the growth trend with a 2.1
percent increase while Luxembourg saw a negative growth of 0.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Spain, Finland and France were above the union average
for industrial production growth while Britain, Italy and
Luxembourg were well below the union average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
