<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian News Agency's Director, Editor Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Managing Director of
the Iranian official news agency IRNA Mohammad Reza Sadeq and
editor of social news desk Ali Reza Khosravi were detained on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agency reported that the arrest warrant was issued by a
judicial official at Tehran's public court following a complaint
lodged by head of the Foundation for the Oppressed and Disabled
Mohsen Rafiqdoust for a report on the assassination attempt on his
life on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Sadeq and Khosravi were interrogated for five hours at the
public court and then detained, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, IRNA did not give the details about Rafiqdoust's
complaint against the agency's official and editor.
</P>
<P>
Unknown gunmen opened fire on Rafiqdoust from a hill
overlooking his office at the headquarters of the foundation, but
Rafiqdoust escaped the assassination without any injury.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time within 10 days pressmen were arrested in
Iran following a warning by supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
against the tendency of "freedom abuse" in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the moderate daily Tous, which was named after an
ancient Iranian city, was banned and some editors of the daily
detained by the conservative judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were
killed and three others wounded in south Lebanon Tuesday by a
Lebanese guerrillas' roadside bomb, the official National News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The remote-controlled bomb exploded when a patrol of Israeli
soldiers passed by the village of Dir Sarayan on the edge of the
Israeli occupied security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack, saying one of its guerrilla units
detonated the bomb.
</P>
<P>
But, Israeli army said in a statement that the soldiers were
killed and wounded when the tank they were riding turned over at
the village, calling it an "accident."
</P>
<P>
The agency said following the incident that Israeli helicopters
arrived at the site and took the casualties to the Israeli
territory.
</P>
<P>
The fresh attack has brought to 14 the number of Israeli
soldiers killed in south Lebanon so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 to protect its north from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been engaged in a war of attrition trying to oust
Israeli troops and their proxy militia South Lebanon Army out of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Parties Slam Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African
opposition parties, except for the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP),
were sharply critical of the government's military intervention
in the neighboring Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Speaking immediately after Acting President Mangosuthu
Buthelezi had briefed the parliament on the issue, the National
Party foreign affairs spokesman Boy Geldenhuys said on Tuesday
South Africa's intervention was short-sighted.
</P>
<P>
It had serious implications for South Africa's future
relations with the mountain kingdom, he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Party expressed sympathy to South African
soliders injured and condolences to the families of those killed.
</P>
<P>
At least five South African soliders were killed and more than
10 others wounded when some 600 South African peacekeeping troops
crossed into Lesotho Tuesday morning to help restore stability in
Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
"We also wish to convey our apology to the people of Lesotho,"
Geldenhuys said.
</P>
<P>
The National Party urged the South African government to
immediately pull out its forces and to facilitate a new general
election in Lesotho under international supervision.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen expressed
dissatisfaction with the fact that Buthelezi had read out a
letter from the Lesotho government dated September 16 asking for
aid, but South African parties were only being informed of
this after the event.
</P>
<P>
Viljoen, a former South African defense force chief, said the
Lesotho Defense Force should take over in that country and the
South African troops be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
He also questioned the constitutionality of South Africa's
intervention, saying he did not think a request to the Southern
African Development Community could be regarded as enough of an
international obligation.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon said South Africa's
intervention had made a political resolution of Lesotho's
problems more difficult, with opposition parties there saying the
chances of a breakthrough in peace talks was now less possible.
</P>
<P>
However, the IFP, the largest black opposition party in South
Africa, insisted that South Africa's intervention was a right
choice.
</P>
<P>
Acting President Mangasuthu Buthelezi, top leader of the IFP,
said that South Africa's intervention was aimed at restoring law
and order and to support the legitimate government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
