<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Sends Letter to U.N. Chief on Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has brought the issue
of recent destruction of cultural and religious heritage in
Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus to the attention of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. chief, published here Tuesday, Cyprus'
permanent representative to the U.N. Sotos Zakheos noted that the
Church of Saint Theodoros in the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
village of Lapithos was vandalized after being abandoned and
desecrated.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Shrine of Saint Kourmoutas in Lapithos has
been profaned and defiled.
</P>
<P>
"The documented large-scale destruction of over 500 churches,
which continues unabated, is an effort to turkify the occupied
areas," Zakheos said.
</P>
<P>
He said that this was done "in violation of the 1954
Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event
of Armed Conflict and the Declaration of the Principles of
International Cultural Cooperation, adopted by the General
Conference of the UNESCO (United Nations Educational, Scientific
and cultural Organization) in 1966."
</P>
<P>
Zakheos said that despite the zealous protection of places of
worship belonging to all faiths by the Cypriot government, Turkey
"has been resolute in its policy of religious intolerance in the
occupied areas and refuses to adhere to international law and the
relevant U.N. resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the other gross violations against religious,
cultural and historical monuments, reported to you in previous
correspondence, Turkey, as the occupying power for more than 24
years, is entirely accountable and fully answerable for these new
illegal and wanton acts of vandalism," the Cypriot diplomat
said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 35 Percent of Zambians Die Before 40: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) said in a report Tuesday about 35
percent of Zambia's population die before 40 years of age due to
poverty, according to Zambia News Agency (ZANA).
</P>
<P>
In its report released here, the UNDP also said that by 1999,
35.1 percent of the total Zambian population were expected to be
wiped out before age 40 as most citizens lived below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
The Development Cooperation Report for Zambia which was handed
over to Finance and Economic Development Minister, Edith Nawakwi,
further added that as a result of this, poverty was the most
worrisome problem in Zambia today.
</P>
<P>
More than two thirds of the 9.5 million Zambians are said to
be living below the poverty line and the per capita income in the
country continued to drop with a fall of 1.1 percent registered
in 1996, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Besides poverty, the report also attributed the short life
expectancy to poor access to safe water in the country, with 73
percent of the population having no access at all.
</P>
<P>
However, it said due to these grim observations, the Zambian
government had set several objectives for national development
with reduction of poverty being one of the issues on the top of
its agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts on Cyprus to Continue: U.S. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Presidential
Emissary for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke has stated that he will
continue his efforts to push for a bizonal, bicommunal federation
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke voiced his resolution after a meeting Tuesday in New
York with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides, who is attending the
53rd U.N. General Assembly there, Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said that he will continue to serve as the U.S.
envoy for Cyprus pending the confirmation process for his
nomination as U.S. permanent representative to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke was nominated earlier this year as the U.S. permanent
representative to the U.N. to replace Ambassador Bill Richardson.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke noted that he will "gradually phase out of the direct
full-time responsibility (in Cyprus), but will remain very actively
involved."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway republic
in northern Cyprus, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the island
through a bi-communal federation formula.
</P>
<P>
But the peace talks have been deadlocked since a year ago when
Turkish Cypriots opted out of the negotiations to protest against
a decision by the European Union (EU) to start accession talks
with Cyprus, not their close ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has recently proposed to
establish a Cyprus confederation of two equal states as a basis
for resuming peace talks, but this has been rejected by the
Cypriot government dominated by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke reiterated that "we support a bizonal, bicommunal
federation and there has been no change whatsoever in our
position."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke also said he will meet Clerides again later this week
and is expected to hold talks with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem and Denktash who is due in New York next week.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus government spokesman Christos Stylianides has described
the Clerides-Holbrooke meeting as "very useful" toward a solution to
the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho FM Defends Foreign Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Foreign
Minister Tom Thabane Tuesday defended the presence of South
African and Botswana troops in his country, saying they were
forced to fight a war.
</P>
<P>
"They didn't come to fight a war, but rather (to) stabilize
the situation so that we could sit down and talk," South African
Press Association (SAPA) quoted Thabane as saying in an interview
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, anti-government elements were not interested in
peace, but wanted war, Thabane said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
forces in Lesotho had to intensify their actions, while their
political masters had to do away with basic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
Thabane acknowledged that SADC and the Lesotho government
misjudged the response from anti-government protesters, including
troops loyal to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We did not foresee it. We knew a lot of people were opposed,
but we did think there would be peaceful overtures."
</P>
<P>
Thabane said opposition supporters systematically destroyed
the homes of Lesotho ministers in Maseru and the private
residence of Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili in neighboring
Roma.
</P>
<P>
Thabane's own home was also among those targeted by
anti-government protesters.
</P>
<P>
"They hit it with a bazooka. There was a hole and then they
firebombed it. Nothing was saved. I'm very angry. I've lost
everything, all my papers."
</P>
<P>
The residences of the ministers of finance and education and
Mosisili's house in Roma were also razed, Thabane said.
</P>
<P>
After his house was attacked, Thabane rejected proposed talks
with opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
He said he was not sure he was prepared to talk to people who
burned his home. "How can we have talks when you burn my house?"
he asked.
</P>
<P>
He said the burning of government homes was criminal, not
political.
</P>
<P>
South African forces TucIe*\
=U9QInexpected strong
resistance from Lesotho soldiers and civilians. So far five South
African soldiers have lost their lives in fighting.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 South African National Defense Force personnel
crossed the border early Tuesday morning to try to restore order
in the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The mission was part of a SADC operation which also involved
about 200 Botswana troops.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho was plunged into anarchy by opposition party
supporters who stopped civil servants from going to work and
hijacked government vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The seven-week-old crisis in Lesotho resulted from the
opposition's dissatisfaction with the outcome of the May 23
general election.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties believed that the election was rigged in
favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy which won 79
of 80 seats in parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
