<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Calls for Fair South-North Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Ghana Tuesday called
for fair relations between developing countries and developed
nations because no nation "can play outside the rules" and no
country "can stand alone."
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Ghana's President J. Rawlings was
addressing the 53rd session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"The present approach of certain industrialized countries which
require of developing countries standards or policies which they
themselves do not observe, or seem unable to, will severely test
the state of relations between the developed and developing world
in the next century," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"We must stand together if we are not to jeopardize the
prosperity enjoyed by the hundreds of millions today and the hopes
of billions more for a life of dignity and comfort," he said.
</P>
<P>
Policy makers and opinion leaders in the developed countries
bear great responsibility in this regard in providing clear
leadership, for those countries share a great part of the blame
for the present state of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even though it had been clear for some time now that
sustainable development across the globe could not be achieved
without a measure of fairness in the economic relations between
the north and the south, because of short term considerations of
profit and advantage the countries benefitting from the unjust
economic order chose to ignore the serious impact of that
situation on living standards in most parts of the world as well
as in limiting world economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
On African economy, the president said, "the persistent
critical economic situation in African should be of great concern
to the international community and should urge us all to take
effective and urgent measures to address its underlying causes."
</P>
<P>
Many African countries, particularly the poorer ones, "continue
to suffer from a heavy burden and crippling debt servicing
obligations which, by diverting resources away from development,
prevent us from providing adequate social services to our
populations in basic areas such as education and health, and
reduce our capacity to compete in the global market," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, we stress the need for debt relief measures to
be accompanied by concessional financial assistance, particularly
to the least developed countries, with the aim of enhancing the
implementation of economic reforms, and creating a stable
environment that enables countries to extricate themselves from
the debt overhang," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
