<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 of those
Eritrean family members who stayed behind in Ethiopia are now
ready to join their family members in Eritrea, according to a
government statement issued here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of claims to the contrary by the Eritrean
government, the Ethiopian government was not seeking to divide
families but was allowing them time to dispose of their property
and arrange their affairs." the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Ethiopia has asked the International
Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) to monitor this process of family
reunion in its entirety," it said, adding that "the ICRC has
preferred to limit its involvement, for logistical reasons, to
the start of travel in Ethiopia and to arrival at the Eritrean
border."
</P>
<P>
"The government of Ethiopia takes this opportunity to
reiterate its call upon the international community, including
the United Nations, to ensure that Ethiopians in Eritrea -- most
particularly in Assab -- are assisted to escape from the tragic
conditions they are being forced to face," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea says up to 17,000 of its nationals have been expelled
from Ethiopia since the border dispute between the two countries
erupted in May, this year. But Ethiopia says those deported for
security reasons were only around 4,000.  
