<HEADLINE> Iran Favors Diplomatic Solution to Dispute With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (xinhua) -- Iran was trying to
prevent a war between Iran and Afghanistan, and Iran welcomed U.N.
moves to promote a diplomatic settlement, Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference with Western reporters, Khatami,
who is here to attend the 53rd session of the General Assembly,
said "Iran is ready to defend its security and territorial
integrity, but it is trying to make all efforts so that there will
not be a war."
</P>
<P>
The president said the eight-power meeting at the United
Nations Monday had taken acceptable steps to remove the problem in
a diplomatic way.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "We have deep concern about the Taliban, so no
matter how much diplomatic effort there is, it will not be in
proportion to the concern we have."
</P>
<P>
The most immediate concern was to prevent a massacre of
defenseless people living in the regions captured by the Taliban,
Khatami noted.
</P>
<P>
The eight-power meeting, initiated by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, urged the Taliban and other parties in Afghanistan to
declare an immediate cease-fire and undertake negotiations to
achieve a political settlement culminating in the establishment of
a broad-based, multi-ethnic, representative government in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also called for an international investigation into
the killing of Iranian diplomats and United Nations staff in
Afghanistan. 
</P>
