<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Small Parties, Big Roles in German Election  (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- With opinion polls show that
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's party is closing the gap with the
rival Social Democrats (SPD), the small German parties have become
critical in deciding the outcome of the country's upcoming general
elections.
</P>
<P>
With the national vote just five days away, German polls put
the support rates for Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU)
party and the main opposition SPD both at about 40 percentage
points, with the CDU trailing the latter by only two to three
points, far less than the 12 points registered in April this year.
</P>
<P>
It was the closest election race in Germany's post-war era,
German pollsters said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, 68, has been leading a center-right ruling coalition --
consisting of the CDU, its Bavarian sister party, the Christian
Social Union (CSU), and the junior coalition partner, the Free
Democratic Party (FDP) -- uninterruptedly since 1982.
</P>
<P>
He is already the longest-serving German chancellor since 1945
and Europe's most durable statesman.
</P>
<P>
Pinning his hope on a large number of undecided voters, Kohl
has stressed that he has good chance to make it again this time.
</P>
<P>
A serious challenge, however, comes from Gerhard Schroeder, the
54-year-old SPD chancellor candidate and a political fresh face,
who many analysts say represents a broad public desire for change
after 16 years of rule by Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Riding on a public outcry about the near-record high
unemployment and a reform standstill in Germany, Schroeder, who
pledges to adopt policies to combine modernity with social justice
in Germany, is leading Kohl all the way since last year in opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
However, as the election draws near, it seems more likely that
neither Kohl nor Schroeder would win absolute majority in order to
govern alone, thus making it necessary for a ruling coalition with
the smaller parties as was the case in most of Germany's post-war
history.
</P>
<P>
The future lineup of the German government will hinge on
whether the smaller parties, such as the ecologist Greens, the
pro-business FDP, and the Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS)
which grew out of the former East German Communist Party, would
get into parliament, German commentators said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Small Parties, Big Roles in German Election  (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under Germany's proportional representation voting system, a
party needs to score at least five percent of the votes in order
to win any seats in the federal parliament, a hurdle designed to
promote political consensus and prevent weak governments.
</P>
<P>
According to opinion polls, all of the small German parties are
hovering at the dangerous point: the Greens at six or seven
points, the FDP at around five percent and the PDS at about four.
</P>
<P>
The FDP, the traditional kingmaker in German politics, has been
in every German government for nearly 30 years, first in alliance
with the SPD and then with Kohl's conservatives since 1982.
</P>
<P>
But the party known for its pro-free-market policies has seen
its public support dip sharply in the past decade and has been
kept out 12 of the country's 16 state parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, however, say that he will only rule with the FDP, no
other small parties.
</P>
<P>
The Greens, founded in 1980 and replaced the FDP as the third
strongest party in Germany in 1994, are hoping to come to power
this time in alliance with the SPD.
</P>
<P>
But they have also lost support heavily since earlier this year
after making a series of radical demands, including a call to
triple gasoline prices over a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that a possible SPD-Greens coalition would
largely depend on the fate of the PDS.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing party, which is supported mainly by East Germans,
got 30 seats in the German parliament in the 1994 vote by winning
three voting districts outright, an alternative condition to get
into parliament if a party falls short of the five-percent hurdle.
</P>
<P>
The PDS has said it wants to enter the federal parliament again
by winning four direct mandates this time.
</P>
<P>
If it failed, the SPD and the Greens might be able to muster
the majority to govern. But if the party made it, a SPD-Greens
government would have to count on the support from the PDS, a
possibility that has been ruled out by Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, it has been widely speculated
the two largest parties, the CDU and the SPD, might be forced to
form a so-called "grand coalition" between themselves, something
Germany has not seen since 1969.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls show such a "grand coalition" is increasingly
popular with the German voters who want some political change
after 16 years of Kohl but meanwhile fear too much risks.
</P>
<P>
The SPD candidate Schroeder has not ruled out leading such a
grand coalition government but Kohl has said he does want to do
that.
</P>
<P>
In such an event, Kohl has noted that he would rather step down
and make the way for his anointed successor and CDU parliamentary
leader Wolfgang Schaeuble. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
