<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Urged to Take Part in Making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China said Tuesday
that developing countries need to increase their capacity to
participate effectively in the formulation of new "rules of game"
in multilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
This is a way to safeguard their legitimate interests, said
Shen Guofang, Chinese deputy permanent representative to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the second session of the Council of Representatives
of the South Center, Ambassador Shen said that for many developing
countries, the external economic environment continues to worsen.
</P>
<P>
The prices for primary commodities are in a downward spiral,
causing serious damage on exporting developing nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries are turning more and more to trade
protectionism, while environmental and labor standards are
becoming new non-tariff barriers targeted at the products from
developing countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Developed nations, with their dominance of world economy, are
promoting selective new areas of trade liberalization, and are
pressuring developing countries to shoulder responsibilities
beyond their levels of development, thus putting new restraints to
their development efforts, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
Praising the South Center for its function of promoting
South-South cooperation and South-North dialogue, Shen called on
the center to continue to serve as a think-tank for developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
The South Center, headquartered in Geneva, is an
inter-governmental body set up in 1995, with 46 countries as its
members.
</P>
<P>
Its main objectives include experience exchange between member
states and the provision of information, research on the current
international issues and policy recommendations to member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
