<HEADLINE> Obuchi Says His Talks With Clinton "Very Candid" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi Tuesday held what he called "very candid" talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton about his country's efforts to carry
out economic and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, both in New York for the opening of the 53rd
session of the U.N. General Assembly, met privately for about one
hour at New York's Waldorf Astoria Hotel.
</P>
<P>
They had been scheduled to meet at the Rockefeller family
estate north of the city, but bad weather forced them to cancel
the trip.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the one-to-one discussions with
Clinton, Obuchi said that he and the U.S. president reviewed the
current global crisis and Japan's efforts to deal with the
situation.
</P>
<P>
"We talked in a very candid manner," Obuchi told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he understood that the government of the new
Japanese prime minister can only do what is "politically possible"
to deal with the worst economic problems in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The discussions were followed by broader discussions among
officials from both countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the U.S. and Japanese leaders is widely believed
to be very important to easing Asia's crisis and stabilizing world
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, senior U.S. economic and financial officials
have been urging Japan to be more aggressive in carrying out
economic reforms, particularly in financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Washington says that the earlier recovery of the troubled
Japanese economy is essential to helping other Asian nations out
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the one-to-one discussions, Clinton invited Obuchi to
come back for a formal state visit some time next year.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi succeeded Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto this summer.
Hashimoto was forced to resign because of growing unhappiness over
his handling of the economic problems. 
</P>
