<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Start Compulsory Inspection on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Traffic
Police Department said Tuesday that it will start a compulsory
inspection on vehicles across the country Friday in a bid to
reduce traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the department said that passenger
buses, lorries, pick-ups and other service automobiles will be
inspected and those which are not roadworthy are to be stopped
from operating.
</P>
<P>
During the inspection, a driver should come with his or her
automobile together with driving license, original registration
card of the automobile, uniform, identification badge, insurance
premium certificate and receipt, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Vehicles which will not be sent for inspection by October 25
will not be allowed to drive on road," it said.
</P>
<P>
Even with relatively fewer motor vehicles, Tanzanian drivers
caused 23 times more accidents than their British counterparts,
statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government launched a road safety week from
September 14 to September 20, following reports that 5,098 people
were killed and 37,624 others were injured in more than 42,000
road accidents during the past three years.  
</P>
