<HEADLINE> Lesotho King Took Side in Conflict: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Prime Minister
Pakalitha Mosisili said Tuesday that he was unable to consult
King Letsie III about a request for foreign military
intervention, because the king was part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mosisili as
saying in an interview that the king harbored anti-government
protesters in the grounds of his royal palace for seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho king was purely ceremonial and was not allowed to
interfere in politics.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili denied claims that he acted unconstitutionally by
requesting military intervention from his Southern African
Development Community (SADC) allies.
</P>
<P>
"I used the Lesotho Defense Force ACT, which empowers me as
minister of defense to invite foreign forces."
</P>
<P>
There was nothing in his country's constitution saying that
the head of state should be the one to invite foreign troops to
restore order, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili asked twice in writing for urgent SADC military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
South African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi
said Tuesday that a virtual coup in Lesotho prompted South
Africa's military action.
</P>
<P>
He said information received by Monday night indicated that a
coup has occurred.
</P>
<P>
Mutineers were in charge of the military and they refused to
take orders form the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The general situation in Lesotho had become ungovernable with
the police paralyzed against lawlessness such as looting,
Mufamadi said.
</P>
<P>
About 600 South African soldiers were sent to Lesotho Tuesday
morning to try to restore order in Lesotho's capital Maseru. So
far five soldiers have been killed in fighting with Lesotho
civilians and soldiers loyal to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 Botswana troops were also dispatched, but arrived
only late Tuesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
