<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned Congo Fighting Spread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
expressed grave concern Tuesday about credible reports that more
countries are involved in the fighting in Congo.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Sudan and Chad have become involved
along with former Rwandan Army members and Hutu extremists, known
as Interhamwe, spokesman James Rubin said at a regular State
Department briefing.
</P>
<P>
These forces supplement those from Rwanda, Uganda, Angola,
Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. calls for all foreign forces to withdraw from the
Congo, and urges countries and armed movements not currently
engaged in the conflict to "desist from intervening," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the United States especially deplores
reported efforts by the Congolese government to enlist support of
Rwandan fighters linked to the genocide.
</P>
<P>
"The involvement of these ethnically motivated killers would
have extremely serious consequences, including fomenting the
resurgence of genocide," Rubin said. 
</P>
