<HEADLINE> Kohl: Grand Coalition With SPD Possible in Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- As Germany's national election
set to be a close race, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said
Wednesday it is possible in principle for the country's two
largest political parties to form a grand coalition government,
but he is still against such an idea.
</P>
<P>
"I naturally reckon a grand coalition possible in principle,"
Kohl said in an interview with the German ZDF television network.
He added that it was quite normal for democratic parties to be
able to form a coalition with each other.
</P>
<P>
However, Kohl stressed that he did not expect a grand coalition
between his Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) after the September 27
elections.
</P>
<P>
"A strong government needs a strong opposition," Kohl said,
adding he did not believe that a government which holds 90 percent
majority in parliament would do a productive job.
</P>
<P>
Speculations about a possible grand coalition take the center
stage in the German media recently as many commentators predict
that neither the CDU nor the SPD would be able to muster a
majority in parliament even in alliance with their respective
partners, the Free Democratic Party (FDP) and the Greens.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's challenger, the SPD chancellor candidate Gerhard
Schroeder, has never ruled out leading a grand coalition with the
CDU, but Kohl has said repeatedly that he wants no part of it.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who is running for a record fifth term in office,
reiterated Wednesday that he would not lead such a coalition and
also did not expect his CDU to join a SPD-led government as a
junior partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
