<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Moves Against Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Struggles in Nepal over the
Local Autonomy Bill heated up again Wednesday as the main
opposition sought to remove the Lower House speaker from office by
registering a motion against him.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-
UML), which blocked the house session by shouting slogans, alleged
that Speaker Ram Chandra Poudel could not discharge his duty in a
fair and impartial manner.
</P>
<P>
K. P. Oli, a key member of the CPN-UML, told the house session
Wednesday that the role played by the speaker in passing the bill
in the house last Thursday was against the parliamentary
democratic system, so his party was compelled to register the
motion.
</P>
<P>
When the opposition MPs, who had blocked the house session for
four days, were voicing their protest against the Local Autonomy
Bill, Speaker Poudel conducted voice voting on the bill and
declared that it had been passed by the house.
</P>
<P>
Then the MPs of the ruling and opposition parties manhandled
one another and caused seven MPs from the CPN-UML injured. In
addition, chairs and microphones valued at about 500,000 rupees
(about 7,460 U.S. dollars) were damaged in the manhandling.
</P>
<P>
The next day, the CPN-UML alleged that "the speaker created an
abnormal and violent situation in parliament and showed his
incompetence, arrogant and undemocratic attitude."
</P>
<P>
It charged that the speaker, who is from the ruling Nepali
Congress (NC), had failed to manage the crisis and rise above the
party politics when executing the house procedures.
</P>
<P>
The party, which sought but failed to add into the bill a
provision that automatically terminates one's post if a locally
elected official defects to another party, had announced that it
would not accept the bill.
</P>
<P>
It fears that with the passage of the bill, more of its local
workers may defect to the Communist Party of Nepal
(Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), which broke away from it in March this
year and joined the government late last month.
</P>
<P>
It takes one week for the motion to be mature before the house
can discuss it.
</P>
<P>
A two-third majority is needed in the house to force its
speaker out of power.
</P>
<P>
But the motion is sure to be defeated in the 205-seat house
where the NC and the CPN-ML enjoy a comfortable majority of at
least 128 seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NC and the CPN-ML registered a similar motion
against Deputy Speaker Lila Shrestha Subba who is from the CPN-
UML.
</P>
<P>
Her fate is unpredictable as her party cannot muster a two-
third majority in the house to defeat the motion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
