<HEADLINE> Iraq's Non-Cooperation Intolerable: U.S. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. ambassador to
Kuwait James Larocco said Wednesday that Iraq's non-cooperation
with the United Nations will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) quoted Larocco as saying "the
non-cooperation of the Iraqi regime has been happening for quite a
long time. This is something we are vigilant about all the time."
</P>
<P>
This move will not be tolerated, "not now or in the future," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Larocco's words were made to reporters at the launching of a
U.S. marine training exercise, featuring landing, deployment in
the desert and live fire exercises near the Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,500 U.S. marines participated in the unilateral
war game, part of the U.S.-Kuwaiti defense cooperation agreement,
and will spend the next few weeks in the desert.
</P>
<P>
Iraq suspended its cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors on
August 5, which led to a U.N. decision to stop the regular review
of the economic sanctions, imposed on Iraq following its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The weapons inspections began in 1991 after the Gulf War, which
ended the seven-month Iraq's occupation of Kuwait, to ensure Iraq
eradicates all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Larocco said Iraq's suspension of cooperation with the U.N. "is
a violation of the U.N. Security Council resolutions and this is
something the U.N. must take up with the Iraqi regime."
</P>
<P>
In response to questions about contingency plans, the U.S.
ambassador said, "there are always contingency plans, the fact is
we are pursuing a diplomatic option at this time and we will
continue to do so, there are no options off the table."  
</P>
</TEXT>
