<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Mourns PAL Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Wednesday mourned the loss of Philippine Airlines (PAL) hours
before its scheduled shutdown at midnight after 57 years of
service.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada told reporters that he had already
done all he could to save the airline from closing down.
</P>
<P>
"I have already exhausted all remedies to settle this dispute
between labor and management so if they do not agree by midnight,
everything is over. PAL is lost," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier press briefing, Estrada's spokesman Jerry Barican
said the government was saddened with the loss of Asia's first
airline.
</P>
<P>
Barican also said the government is no longer too hopeful that
last-minute talks between labor and management can save the
airline after PAL employees voted against an ownership-sharing
scheme Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senator John Osmena lambasted radical PAL union leaders for the
airline's impending closure, saying their stubbornness caused
great harm to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management last week decided to shut down the airline
after PAL unions rescinded an earlier agreement with the
management and refused to accept the co-ownership plan in exchange
for a 10-year suspension on collective bargaining agreements
(CBA).
</P>
<P>
PAL's management said that with no fresh capital infusion, the
airline could not operate viably in the face of enormous losses
amid the harsh business environment.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of CBA, which is expected to guarantee
industrial peace and harmony in PAL, is a key requirement for any
rehabilitation plan to revive the debt-ridden company.
</P>
<P>
Osmena cited a letter PAL union leaders had presented to
management, in which they laid down difficult conditions.
</P>
<P>
Among the conditions were a yearly review of employees'
salaries, the maintenance of PAL's grievance mechanism, the
maintenance of benefits for employees and the maintenance of the
present work force.
</P>
<P>
Osmena said these conditions were "outrageous," noting that
normal collective bargaining agreements provide for a review of
salaries every three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
