<HEADLINE> Flood-damaged Railway Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A railway line in northeast
China reopened today after being paralyzed by the summer floods
for more than 40 days.
</P>
<P>
Repairing the flood-damaged railway linking the city of Qiqihar in
Heilongjiang Province with Siping in neighboring Jilin
Province took 24 days and the efforts of more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, severe flooding of the Nenjiang River destroyed
three sections of the rail bed to a length of two kilometers,
knocking out the line.
</P>
<P>
Repairs were completed four days ahead of schedule due to
the efficiency of local railway authorities. 
</P>
