<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia Wednesday expressed
regret over the decision of the Finnish authorities to expel two
Russian diplomats on charges of espionage, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Russian Foreign Ministry confirmed that
some time ago, Finland informed Russia through diplomatic channels
that two Russian embassy officials in Helsinki had been declared
persona non grate for activities incompatible with their
diplomatic status.
</P>
<P>
The press department of the ministry was quoted as saying that
"the decision perplexed Moscow."
</P>
<P>
According to news reports reaching here, the Finnish
authorities have meanwhile filed a criminal charge against a
high-ranking Finnish diplomat, who is suspected of having given
secret information on the European Union to the two Russian
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Finland officially confirmed on Wednesday that the two Russian
diplomats had already left Helsinki, one of them about six months
ago, and the other in August.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry said that "the Russian side
stated that it was an apparent misunderstanding and expressed the
hope that the Finnish authorities' decision would be reversed."
