<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Eyes Manageable Disruption From PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
hopes to keep the economic losses caused by the impending closure
of Philippine Airlines (PAL) as manageable as possible, the
Presidential News Desk said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We think we can keep the disruption to the economy to at least
a level we can manage," Presidential spokesman Jerry Barican in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the government expects that the economic harm to
be caused by the airline's closure, which is scheduled for
midnight Wednesday, will be limited.
</P>
<P>
He said other domestic airlines had been given 25 days to take
over PAL's domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the damage would only be similar to that caused by
an earlier strike by the PAL Employees Association (PALEA) which
lasted 22 days.
</P>
<P>
Economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla said the extent of
the losses would depend on how quickly other airlines can expand
their services.
</P>
<P>
Economists here have warned that the shutdown of PAL, the
country's only major airline, is expected to do much harm to the
economy since other domestic airlines are small and aviation is
vital for the archipelago country.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said PAL's closure may hike
interest rates on non-performing loans by 0.5 to 0.7 percent, but
added that this was still a safe margin.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu also said the government plans to collect its
investments from PAL once the airline files an application for
dissolution.
</P>
<P>
"The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) will appoint
independent members (of an interim receivership committee) once
PAL closes," he said.
</P>
<P>
PAL's management announced last week that PAL will close down
at the midnight of Wednesday after the unions refused to accept an
ownership-sharing scheme for a 10-year suspension on their
collective bargaining agreement (CBA).
</P>
<P>
The management said the loss-making airline could not continue
its operations due to its devastating financial situation
aggravated by the currency crisis and a series of strikes by its
employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
