<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Annuls Frauded Recruitment Examination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
annulled on Wednesday its recruitment examination that had been
alleged to be rife with frauds.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, made the decision after reviewing a report by European
Personnel Administration Commissioner Erkki Liikanen.
</P>
<P>
Liikanen said in his report that annulment had to be initiated
after sufficient evidence had so far been amassed to prove that
there had been wrongdoings prior to and during the examination
that took place on September 14.
</P>
<P>
The commission organized its recruitment examination in 38
testing centers scattered in the 15 EU member states. A total of
31,000 applicants sat in the examination that was designed to
serve as a pre-selection process.
</P>
<P>
But after the examination, the commission received, especially
from Rome and Brussels, complaints that some examination takers
had resorted to illegal means to get an upper-hand edge.
</P>
<P>
The means complained about included the use of mobile
telephones and pre-examination tips and leaks from examination
organizers.
</P>
<P>
Liikanen suggested to the commission that the results of the
recruitment examination be scrapped and a new recruitment
examination be organized for the candidates as soon as the
investigation into the fraud is complete.
</P>
<P>
The recruitment examination, aimed at recruiting some 2,000
commission staff workers, cost the commission 1.2 million ECUs
(1.32 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set Ticket Prices for Tourism Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China will standardize
ticket prices for tourism sites in an effort to curb illegal
practices, according to information released during a recent
national conference.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference, which was closed on Tuesday in
Chongqing, reached a consensus that prices should be set in line
with the services and quality of tourism sites.
</P>
<P>
The central government will set prices for famous sites, with
local governments responsible for setting prices for other
holiday resorts.
</P>
<P>
Resort will be required to charge one price for entrance
tickets, and will be required to obtain approval from pricing
departments in order to charge extra fees for special on-site
attractions.
</P>
<P>
Ticket pricing regulations will be formulated by the State
Development Planning Commission and other concerned
departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
