<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Prepares for PAL Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
started implementing emergency measures to minimize the economic
disruption to be caused by the closure of Philippine Airlines
(PAL) at midnight on Wednesday, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu
said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the government has received commitments from at
least four local airlines to immediately expand their operations
so they can ply the domestic routes which PAL will abandon
starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said Air Philippines, Cebu Pacific, Asian Spirit and
GrandAir have pledged to upgrade their capacity from 230,000 to
510,000 passengers within the next 25 to 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said Air Philippines also pledged to obtain two
foreign McDonnell-Douglas aircraft, complete with crew members,
within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Senator John Osmena, who attended a meeting called by President
Joseph Estrada with congressional leaders in an effort to save
PAL, also disclosed that the Civil Aeronautic Board will allow
foreign airlines to ply domestic routes in emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to see to it that we are able to immediately
cover the vacuum that will be there over the next few days," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the government is also ready to speed up the
entry of other airlines that will fill in the void left by PAL,
particularly the domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Jerry Barican disclosed that the Labor
Department is supervising last-minute conciliation talks between
PAL's management and its workers.
</P>
<P>
PAL's management last week decided to cease operations at
midnight of Wednesday after PAL unions refused to accept a
co-ownership offer and push through a rebuilding plan to save the
debt-ridden airline.
</P>
<P>
Under the offer, the unions would get 20 percent of shares of
PAL in exchange for a 10-year suspension on their collective
bargaining agreement, with every employee receiving some 60,000
shares worth 300,000 pesos (6,967 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
