<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Experience Sharing With Mediterranean Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission --
the executive body of the 15-member European Union -- proposed on
Wednesday the sharing of the European Union's single market
experience with its Mediterranean partners.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposed initiatives of experience sharing in
the fields of training, technical assistance, advice and
cooperation in relation to the internal market, customs and
taxation.
</P>
<P>
The initiatives will need discussion and approval by the
European Union and its Mediterranean partners.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that the proposal was designed to
facilitate the creation of a free trade area with the
Mediterranean by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Mediterranean partnership was formed by the Barcelona
Declaration in November 28, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The most important objectives of the EU-Mediterranean
partnership are economic and financial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mario Monti, European single market commissioner, said that the
proposal was to provide the Mediterranean partners with a higher
degree of economic cooperation and concerted action with the aim
of building an area of shared prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He said that the commission was ready to share the experience
it had acquired in setting up the internal market.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to demonstrate to the Mediterranean
partners the advantages of the creation of the EU internal market,
and advantages in terms of growth, competitiveness and job
creation by removing trade barriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
