<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's three refineries will lift their
refining capacity to 1 million barrels per day (bpd) by the year
2002, an oil official said.
</P>
<P>
Riyah Al-Saleh, executive assistant to the managing director
of Kuwait National Petroleum Company (KNPC), was quoted Wednesday
by local English daily the Arab Times as saying that the current
capacity of the three refineries stands at 840,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
Exports account for almost 90 percent of current output from
the three refineries.
</P>
<P>
With an proven oil reserve of nearly 100 billion barrels, or
about 10 percent of the world total oil reserve, Kuwait now enjoys
a production quota of 2.19 million bpd of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A Saudi Arabia-based commercial investment
joint-venture has agreed to acquire majority shares of the
Mediterranean Gulf Insurance and Reinsurance Company (MedGulf) in
Bahrain and Lebanon's MedGulf Strikers Holding (MSH), Kuwait News
Agency (Kuna) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement by Al-Azizia Commercial Investment Company, which
is owned by Saudi Prince Al-Waleed Bin Talal and Lebanese
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri's Mediterranean Investors Group (MIG),
said the partners in the deal have agreed to ensure a high
capitalization for the MedGulf insurance group.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources told Kuna that the deal is estimated
at nearly 66.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the partners will strive for establishing
strategic alliances with international insurance companies to face
up challenges that might result from fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
The deal will allow MedGulf to increase its share in the
insurance market and will give it the ability to provide all
kinds of insurance services in the Gulf and the Middle East areas.
</P>
<P>
The deal will also allow MedGulf to buy a large share of the
booming Saudi insurance market after the enforcement of the
cooperative health insurance system.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- General Manager of "Andalusia Group" in Saudi Arabia
Ra'id Abdul Latif Al Ibrahim has estimated the group's sales of
aluminium in the Saudi market at about 500 million rials (133.3
million U.S. dollars), indicating that the volume of local market
consumption last year stood at some 50,000 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried on Wednesday's Arab daily "Al Hayat,"
Ibrahim said that the group exports its products to the Gulf
Cooperation Council states, Egypt, Algeria and other countries of
the region.
</P>
<P>
The company is one of the largest manufacturers, distributors
and agents of aluminium in Saudi Arabia. It owns each of the
Grenada aluminium, Safa aluminium, Saudi factory for plating
aluminium with timber and marble colors, and Al Ruwad factory for
poly carbon.
</P>
<P>
It is the agent of Italian, Belgian and British companies for
aluminium and glass factory equipment. It is also a shareholder of
a number of aluminium factories together with other companies.
</P>
<P>
It provides over 6,000 types of aluminium and glass
accessories. It further owns a number of trade centers and a
factory for the production of "classic" shoes. The total sales of
the group over the past year amounted to 120 million rials (32
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
