<HEADLINE> Former Israeli Premier Encourages Clinton to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli prime
minister Shimon Peres has encouraged U.S. President Bill Clinton
not to quit from his presidency, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to Clinton on Wednesday, Peres said "The
winner does not quit and quitters are not winners."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's sex scandal has caused a lot of worries in Israel,
which regards Clinton as its strong supporter no matter how the
situation in the Middle East changes.
</P>
<P>
Although the Israeli government takes a cautious stand towards
the Clinton issue, the majority of Israelis support Clinton to
continue to stay in the office, local press reports said.
</P>
<P>
Peres was the first Israeli influential figure expressing open
support to Clinton after Monday's videotaped broadcast of
Clinton's August 17 grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the videotape broadcasting, an opinion poll
conducted by the local media among 500 households on Monday
showed that 80 percent of them said the tape was nothing but an
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
Local English paper the Jerusalem Post said in its Wednesday
editorial that "people throughout the world can not understand why
the U.S. is doing this to itself."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians also expressed their worries about the sex
scandal, which they believe could affect Clinton's policy of
pushing the stalled Mideast peace process forward, even though the
U.S. did not pressure Israel very much in the recent past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
