<HEADLINE> Planning Minister Says China's Economic Target Attainable (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China will be able to realize
its goal of eight percent economic growth this year if the
government's stimulation policies continue to be well implemented,
State Development Planning Minister Zeng Peiyan told a press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the current economic situation in China is good and
the measures the government has taken to expand domestic demand
and stimulate the economy have already started to take effect," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng added that August marked a turning point for the Chinese
economy, as economic indicators showed an upward trend.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the nation's fixed-asset investment growth
has picked up speed, rising 26.9 percent in August over the same
1997 period, 4 percentage points higher than that in July this
year. Consumer goods retail volume in August was up 13 percent,
1.3 percentage points more than in July. Industrial value-added
rose 7.9 percent from the same 1997 period, 0.3 percent higher
than in July.
</P>
<P>
Also, the consumer price index, a major inflation indicator,
rose 0.6 percent over July after a five-month decline, signaling
rebounding domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade sector registered a surplus of 31.3 billion
U.S. dollars during the first seven months of this year, with the
export turnover rising 5.5 percent year-on-year to 118.7 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investment totaled 23.9 billion U.S. dollars,
almost the same as last year, but investment for newly signed
contracts rebounded by 7.3 percent to 28 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planning Minister Says China's Economic Target Attainable (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The money supply also grew, as money in circulation (M0) and
narrow money (M1) increased by 8.6 percent and 10.9 percent
respectively over the first eight months of last year.
</P>
<P>
"It will not be easy for the economy to keep this good momentum
given the worsening Asian financial crisis, and the most severe
summer flooding since 1954," Zeng stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zeng attributed the good economic performance to the
government's timely and stimulating policies, including those
adopted to intensify investment, increase fiscal expenditures,
accelerate extension of bank loans, and expand domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said the summer flooding may cause the
economy to drop one percent this year, but considering the
contribution the reconstruction effort could make to the economy,
the losses are expected to diminish to 0.5 or 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Problems still exist for realizing the annual growth goal,
since the impact of the Asian financial crisis on the economy is
still worsening, and we are faced with the strenuous task of
redeveloping the flooded areas. We need to work even harder to
solve them."
</P>
<P>
To this end, the government will need to guarantee more timely
investment in those key projects already under construction, and
ensure an early start and smooth construction for new projects.
</P>
<P>
A good autumn harvest, further expanded domestic consumption,
and exports are also necessary to reach the growth goal,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Reconstruction of the flooded areas, resettlement of people and
the harnessing of rivers also demands greater effort, which could
offer economic opportunities, Zeng concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
