<HEADLINE> UN Appeal For Disaster Relief For China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The representative offices
of the United Nations' various organizations in Beijing has made
an appeal on behalf of the Chinese government for emergency relief
and assistance for China's flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The UN asked governmental, inter-governmental and private
donors to contribute to the relief efforts of the Chinese
government and the Red Cross after receiving a request from the
Chinese government at the Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs in Geneva. The appeal is based on field
studies done by humanitarian agencies verifying the scale of the
disaster and the urgent need for shelter, food, medical care, and
potable water.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to help 5.8 million people in 9 of the worst hit
areas in Hubei, Jiangxi, Hunan, Guangxi, Anhui, Fujian, Jilin,
Heilongjiang and Inner Mongolia, and to get 139 million
U.S. dollars for shelters, food, health care, water, sanitation,
and emergency repairs for schools and clinics.
</P>
<P>
The appeal covers a four-month period from the end of
September to the end of January 1999. According to Kerstin
Leitner, UN coordinator in China, the UN will probably later look
into longer-term rehabilitation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Ambassador to China James Sasser said that the
U.S. has decided to donate 1.12 million U.S. dollars to China.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the American donation will help
alleviate the hardship of the Chinese flood victims, and said that
the U.S. will also encourage other nations and international
organizations to support the UN appeal, which parallels the appeal
of the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies to the
international community for 13.6 million Swiss francs to purchase
food, water, purification tablets, medicines, sanitation supplies,
quilts, and winter coats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
