<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Remains Most Efficient Air Cargo Hub: Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A manager of Hong Kong's
air cargo terminal said Wednesday that Hong Kong will remain one
of the world's most efficient air cargo hubs despite the bumps and
unwelcome dislocations at the beginning of the operation of the
new airport.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Charter, managing director of Hong Kong Air Cargo
Terminals Ltd. (HACTL), told a gathering of the General Chamber of
Commerce of Hong Kong that Hong Kong is now endowed with an air
cargo terminal that is "certainly the largest, and perhaps the
most sophisticated in the world, capable of handling growth well
into the second decade of the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
After the opening of Hong Kong's new airport at Chek Lap Kok on
July 6, the air cargo services was once dislocated. The new
airport resumed full operation on August 24.
</P>
<P>
Charter said the HACTL is committed to recovering services as
speedily as possible to normal high levels and is "determined to
enhance and broaden" those service standards.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the bumpy start, I am confident that before very
long you will discover that Super Terminal 1 (at the new airport)
is indeed one of the world's most sophisticated and efficient air
cargo handling facilities, providing you with the quality and
efficiency of service that you need to protect and enhance your
competitiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Charter, Hong Kong overtook Narita of Japan in
1996 to become the world's busiest international cargo handling
airport. And the HACTL has also grown to provide one of the
world's most efficient and technologically sophisticated air cargo
handling systems.
</P>
<P>
At Kai Tak, Hong Kong's old airport, where cargo was all
handled in a single complex, "we handled more than that handled by
the 16 airline warehouses combined at Heathrow Airport," Charter
said.
</P>
<P>
The manager believed that Hong Kong's air cargo handling
ability will remain strong in spite of the regional downturn in
trade over the past year as a result of the Asian economic
turmoil, and in spite of the emergence of a number of competitor
hubs around the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the other regional hubs like Taibei or Manila will give
the clients choice and enable them to benchmark the quality and
efficiency of the services Hong Kong gives them. The competition
"will be welcome to all of us." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
