<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scenic Mountains, a Model in Ecological Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Touring on Huangshan Mountains,
one of the noted scenic places in China, visitors are marveled at
its excellent environment and how local people could keep the
ecological balance in such an elegant way.
</P>
<P>
Trees are well cared, many of them protected with bamboo
fences, while dustbins are made in the shape of a tree stake and
handrails assemble tree branches.
</P>
<P>
"We regard trees, stones and all other natural things here as
valuable properties," says an official from the Huangshan Mountains
Scenic Zone Administration. Local people have done their
best to protect the ecological environment while developing a
fledging tourism industry, he says.
</P>
<P>
Located in southern Anhui Province, east China, Huangshan
Mountains is on the Unesco List of World Heritage.
</P>
<P>
After an assessment trip in the area early this month, a two-
member Unesco expert team comes to the conclusion that Huangshan
Mountains could be an example for other World Heritage sites to
follow.
</P>
<P>
"The management of Huangshan Mountains is a miracle," says one
of the experts. The team's work was focused on the ecological
protection, sustained development and diversification of living
things.
</P>
<P>
They agree that local people have made remarkable achievements
in environmental and ecological protection, management in tourism,
protection of various resources, as well as in education of tourists.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, Huangshan Mountains was made a world cultural and
natural heritage by Unesco.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, local authorities have paid much attention to
protecting the ecological environment by bringing into full
consideration the relationship between natural things and man-made
facilities.
</P>
<P>
No trees have been fallen down in road construction and all
tourist facilities have been built in accordance with their
environmental surroundings.
</P>
<P>
Electricity is the only source of energy in the scenic zone as
the use of coal, diesel oil and gas has been banned to reduce
environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
The efforts to maintain an ecological balance have paid
off. The number of tourists has increased by 10 percent annually
in recent years, but the coverage of forests has kept on the rise.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 1.08 million people including 100,000 foreign
nationals visited the zone, while the green coverage reached 87
percent, compared with 56 percent in 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
