<HEADLINE> Modalities for Indo-Pakistan Talks Finalized:Vajpayee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said Wednesday that India and Pakistan had
finalized modalities for resumption of the stalled bilateral
dialogue, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen aboard a special plane on his way to New
York for the 53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly, Vajpayee
said that at his luncheon meeting with his Pakistani counterpart
Nawaz Sharif later Wednesday they would direct their officials to
restart talks on all outstanding issues, including peace and
security and Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretary-level talks between India and Pakistan broke
down last September over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee and Sharif met on the sidelines of a summit of South
Asian leaders in Colombo in July, but failed to reach agreement on
the issue. Sharif termed his meeting with Vajpayee as a waste of
time, while New Delhi responded by saying that Islamabad's focus
on Kashmir was "neurotic."
</P>
<P>
Groundwork for the New York meeting of the two Prime Ministers
was prepared by the foreign secretaries of the two countries when
they met on the fringes of the summit of the non-alignment
movement in Durban, South Africa earlier this month. Their
proposals would be considered by the two Prime Ministers before
the schedule for resumption of the dialogue process is announced,
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
