<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closure Eased, More Palestinians Allowed to Enter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- About 23,000 Palestinians
were allowed to enter Israel as of Wednesday as Israel eased its
closure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip after its Jewish New Year
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army resumed the seal-off last Friday following a
three-day partial lift because the militant Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) threatened to commit terror attacks against
Israel during its three-day Jewish New Year holidays starting
Sunday night to avenge the killing of its two military leaders.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army shot dead Adel and Imad Awadallah brothers on
August 10 near the West Bank town of Hebron and closed the West
Bank and Gaza the following day.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, the closure was once eased and 10,000
Palestinians were given entry into Israel, but the seal-off
resumed following Hamas' threat.
</P>
<P>
It is unclear when the closure will be totally lifted.
</P>
<P>
Tight security measures were imposed across Israel during the
holidays and no terror attacks were reported.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials have said that the closure has
caused a direct loss of 4-5 million U.S. dollars every day to the
Palestinian economy, the indirect damage doubles that amount
and the long-term damage is incalculable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
