<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Hopes Murder Incident Won't Hurt Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Foreign
Minister Jakaya Kikwete Wednesday expressed the hope that the
murder of a Japanese woman by bandits will not damage the
friendship between Tanzania and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a condolence message on behalf of the government at
the funeral ceremony for Rieko Hanaoka, who was shot dead by car
robbers last Thursday, Kikwete said her death has occurred in
circumstances which are "saddening and outrageous."
</P>
<P>
"I want to once again, reiterate, the government's resolve to
track down Rieko's murderers and bring them to justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, held at the Japanese International Cooperation
Agency (JICA) premises in Dar es Salaam, was also attended by the
Minister of Health, Dr. Aaron Chiduo, who denounced and regretted
the "inhuman act."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Ambassador to Tanzania, Keitaro Sato, and JICA
representatives, were also present at the funeral. Japan is a
major donor to the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Hanaoka, 35, was killed by armed bandits attempting to rob her
car outside the gate of her residence in the Mikocheni area in
the northeastern outskirts of Dar es Salaam at around 7:45 p.m.
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The woman was a medical technician with the Maternal and Child
Health Service Project financed by JICA at the Dar es
Salaam-based Muhimbili Medical Center, the largest hospital in
the east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
