<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq: Death Rates Rise Due to Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The death rate of Iraq's
children and elderly has risen significantly due to the crippling
U.N. economic sanctions, official figures said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry statistics published by the Iraqi News Agency
show that 2,917 children under the age of five died of diarrhea
in August, 2,560 cases more than in the same month of 1989.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the sanctions on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait, barring it from exporting oil, its
main revenue earner. This has led to acute shortage of food and
medicine in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said deaths due to lung and respiratory diseases
have risen to 1,191 cases last month from 52 in August 1989. Over
2,600 children died of malnutrition in August, 2,510 more than in
August 1989.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the death toll of the elderly above 50 increased to
466 last month from 81 in August 1989. Deaths due to diabetes
stood at 316 cases, rising by 235 cases. Deaths caused by
malignant tumors increased from 216 cases in August 1989 to 1,375
cases in the same month this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi ministry attributed the high death rate of the
children and the elderly to the acute shortage of food and
medicine, especially among the poor, which has been confirmed by
international organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
