<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Extends Deadline for Party Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Independent
Electoral Commission (NIEC) has extended the exercise of party
registration by 19 days until October 12, media reports said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The extension was announced at a press conference Tuesday in
Abuja, capital of the west African country, by NIEC Chairman
Justice Ephraim Akpata.
</P>
<P>
By the new move, the release of provisionally registered
parties due to out Wednesday will be shifted to October 19.
</P>
<P>
According to guidelines earlier released by the NIEC,
political associations will be registered as true parties only if
they prove their strength in the coming local government
elections by winning at least 25 percent of all votes cast in
each of at least two-thirds of all the 36 states.
</P>
<P>
The NIEC chairman explained that the extension is at the
request of many political associations and will not affect the
time-frame of other activities under the current transition to
civil rule process.
</P>
<P>
By September 9, a total of 25 political associations had
applied to the NIEC for registration.
</P>
<P>
The NIEC has since sent teams nationwide to verify the
associations' claims, including checking the address of their
state secretariats.
</P>
<P>
According to Akpata, it has been found that some associations
have given incorrect addresses which could not be verified and
some even changed their address previously submitted to the NIEC.
</P>
<P>
NIEC sources had described the results of the verification as
poor and disencouraging, adding that in most places visited, only
five associations have identifiable offices and some staff, while
most of the associations are far from meeting NIEC's conditions
for registration.
</P>
<P>
Akpata also called on the associations to mobilize their
supporters for the forthcoming nationwide registration of voters
from October 5 to October 29.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigerian government announced the appointment
of resident electoral commissioners for the 36 states Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They will be inaugurated Friday in Abuja by Akpata, according
to statement by Alhaji Gidado Idris, the Secretary to the
Government of the Federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
