<HEADLINE> UEFA Names All-Star European Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- England teen-ager Michael Owen
and six players from World Cup winner France have been named
Wednesday into a European All-Star line-ups based on their
performance this summer in France.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands, a semifinalist, provided three players into
the first 11, with England and Croatia having one each.
</P>
<P>
The All-Star team was announced at the end of a three-day
conference in Frankfurt of Germeny, A totle of 50 national
coaches from European countries to review the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The All-Star team includes Edwin van der Sar (Netherlands);
Lilian Thuram (France), Marcel Desailly (France), Laurent Blanc
(France), Frank de Boer (Netherlands); Didier Deschamps (France),
Emmanuel Petit (France), Edgar Davids (Netherlands), Zinedine
Zidane (France); Michael Owen (England), Davor Suker (Croatia).
</P>
<P>
While France provided the bulk of the defense and the
midfield, the forward spots went to Owen, one of the most
exciting young players in Europe, and Suker, the Croatian star
scored a tournament high six goals in France.
</P>
<P>
The substitutes are Peter Schmeichel (Denmark); Bixente
Lizarazu (France), Sol Cambell (England), Fernando Hierro
(Spain), Paolo Maldini (Italy); Ronald de Boer (Netherlands),
Robert Jarni (Croatia), David Beckham (England), Zvonimir Boban
(Croatia); Christian Vieri (Italy), Dennis Bergkamp (Netherlands).
</P>
<P>
Aime Jacquet, the coach who guided the French team to the
title, was presented a special UEFA achievement award.
</P>
<P>
The national coaches at the conference also voted to present
an award to Miroslav Blazevic in recognition of his World Cup
campaign at the helm of the Croatian national team, which he
guided to a third-place finish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
