<HEADLINE> West Xia Dynasty Museum Opens in Yinchuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The West Xia Dynasty Museum,
the first of its kind in China, opened today in Yinchuan, capital
of northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 people, including dozens of Chinese and foreign
scholars, attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Dangxiang ethnic minority established the dynasty in
1038. Yinchuan was the capital of the dynasty, which was conquered
by the Yuan dynasty in 1227.
</P>
<P>
The museum, which features numerous cultural relics from the
ancient dynasty, is divided into six sections dedicated to
political, legal, military, social and economic, culture and
economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The museum also offers exhibits outlining the research
achievements of Chinese and foreign scholars and some 413 academic
books and papers concerning the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The museum is located in the West Xia Imperial Tomb Tourism
Zone which is home to nine imperial tombs and over 200 tombs
housing the remains of members of the imperial family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
