<HEADLINE> Arafat Asks Senior Palestinian Negotiator to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat has turned down the resignation of
senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, praising him for his
role in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, Israel Radio reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's rejection came after Erekat, who has led talks
with Israel for the last two years, asked Monday to be
relieved of his post as chief of the Palestinian negotiating
team.
</P>
<P>
In a letter of resignation to Arafat, Erekat said he
wanted to concentrate on his cabinet position in the PNA as
minister of local affairs.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said Erekat is angry that he has been
sidestepped by Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed
Queria (Abu Ala) in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He had held talks with the Israelis on behalf of the
PNA since the two sides resumed direct negotiations in July.
Since mid-August, however, it was reported that Arafat has
beefed up the role of Abu Ala by giving him the job to
talking directly with chief Israeli negotiator Yitzhak Molcho,
personal attorney of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Arafat has asked Erekat to accompany him
to go to the United States later this week when he is due
to attend the United Nations' General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
The radio also said that Molcho has held talks with Abu
Ala and Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) during the
Jewish New Year, which began on Sunday night and ended on
Tuesday night, but no progress has been reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
