<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker in Uncertain Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
weaker Wednesday on an uncertain market.
</P>
<P>
Developments overseas appeared to spell bad news for the local
currency, with traders saying it might have no choice but to ride
out the storm.
</P>
<P>
A foreign exchange manager at Colonial State Bank, Peter
Whitley, said the weaker Japanese yen was a major contributor to
the local currency's problems on the day.
</P>
<P>
"While the world remains in this state of flux in terms of
emerging markets and the problems with Japan's banking system
there is no rush to buy Aussie," he said.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 57.73 US cents, its low for the day,
from Tuesday's close of 58.43.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony
Wednesday night may also have implications for the local currency.
</P>
<P>
"The Aussie could see 57.50 U.S. cents on the downside, if
Greenspan said something in terms of interest rate cuts, then we
might see it back at 58.50, so it could be a big night," Whitley
said.
</P>
<P>
Other international developments include key economic data due
in New Zealand this week.
</P>
<P>
Whitley said New Zealand's rating is already too high, above
that of Australia's, and the market has already factored in a
downgrading of one notch.
</P>
<P>
He said the local market would continue to take direction from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was trading at 78.75 Japanese yen from 78.69
and 0.9707 German marks from 0.9889 previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
