<HEADLINE> Indonesia Team to Release Final Report on May Riots By </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Joint
Fact-Finding Team on the May riots will release its final report
on its findings within the next 30 days, the team's leader Marzuki
Darusman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are now processing the facts and information collected
during our latest searches. We will release our final report to
the public by October 23 at the latest," he said.
</P>
<P>
Part of the team's findings or conclusions might not accord
with the government's, Marzuki said on the sidelines of a
roundtable discussion on "Strategy to Build Indonesia's Overseas
Image" here.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team has been established by the government
to investigate reports that the May riots, in which more than
1,200 people were killed, were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian rights activists have said that 168 women and girls,
most of them ethnic Chinese, were raped or sexually assaulted
during the May riots, and about 20 of them died.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki said his team had told the government at a meeting on
Monday that sexual violence against women did occur during the May
riots. What the team would still try to clarify was the scale of
the violence.
</P>
<P>
"The team's work has not been easy. It was equally difficult to
explain to the government how psychologically painful it is for
the victims to tell their experience to the public," he said.
</P>
<P>
The most important part of his team's task had been devising a
simple method to collect accurate data on the number of the sexual
violence victims without having to actually meet them, Marzuki
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
