<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Supporting China's Clean Fuel Car Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Science
and Technology (MOST) signed an agreement with the U.S.'s Ford
Motor Company to develop alternative fuel vehicles (AFV) here
today.
</P>
<P>
This is the second phase of the Ford China AFV program that was
jointly started by Ford and what was then the State Science and
Technology Commission in May of 1995. The three-year program will
focus on developing compressed natural gas (CNG) and liquefied
petroleum gas (LPG) vehicles in China.
</P>
<P>
The two will jointly develop a prototype CNG diesel dual-fuel
engine, assess the commercial prospects of CNG and LPG cars in
China, develop low-cost auto parts in China, and train Chinese
engineers.
</P>
<P>
Ford already has more than a million alternative fuel vehicles
operating in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, Ford has helped China develop its
first methyl-fuel car and set up a foundation in China to sponsor
research and development of alternative fuel technology.
</P>
<P>
Li Xueyong, the vice-minister of science and technology, said
here today that because China has limited petroleum resources but
an abundant supply of natural gas and coal, natural gas would be
an ideal clean fuel resource.
</P>
<P>
China has over 6,000 alternative fuel vehicles and over 60 CNG
and LPG fueling stations in a dozen major cities. The first CNG
public transport line went into operation in Xi'an in Shaanxi
Province last week.
</P>
<P>
China has plans to build 150 to 200 CNG and LPG fueling
stations and to manufacturer or re-fit 50,000 alternative fuel
vehicles by the end of the century. It has already set up an AFV
technology standardization board to promote development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
