<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Internet Appeal For Donations For China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross Society of
China (RCSC) and the Bank of China have opened a site on the
Internet to solicit donations for flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Donations will go into a special account in the Bank of China
that will be used to help prevent epidemic diseases and build new
houses for people in flooded areas, according to Wang Lizhong,
RCSC's vice-president.
</P>
<P>
He says that the Chinese Red Cross Society will try to use the
donations in accordance with donors' requests on the Internet and
will tell people how the disaster relief is used in the same way.
</P>
<P>
David Aaron, a senior American Commerce Department official who
was at the opening ceremony for the website in Beijing today, said
that it will allow people from around the world to make donations
via the Internet to help Chinese in flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Vast areas along the Yangtze, Nenjiang, and Songhua rivers were
hit by floods this summer, with losses estimated at more than 160
billion yuan (19.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Provincial branches of the RCSC have raised 180 million yuan
worth of cash and material donations for the disaster relief. The
Internet addresses are http:// www.dragonpulse.com;
http://www.chineseredcross.org.cn; http://www.bank-of-china.com;
http://www.cyberash.com; and http//://www.sparkice.com.cn.
</P>
<P>
The activity, which is being sponsored by the American
CyberCash Company and the Unicom-Sparkice Info System Engineering
Ltd, will close at the end of December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
