<HEADLINE> U.S. Asked to Pressure Turkey on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has asked his United States counterpart Bill Clinton to
pressure Turkey into facilitating a solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the request to Clinton in New York at a lunch
hosted by the United Nations chief Kofi Annan for the heads of
state or government attending the 53rd U.N. General Assembly,
Cyprus News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told the news agency
that Clerides briefed Clinton on the latest developments of the
Cyprus problem and asked him to exert pressure on Turkey in a bid
to reach an overall settlement for the issue.
</P>
<P>
Clinton assured that he would seriously consider what Clerides
has said, Stylianides added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is maintaining more than 35,000 troops in northern
Cyprus to protect the Turkish Cypriot minorities.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., alongside other members of the international
community, has been trying to help reunify Cyprus under the
U.N.-sponsored bi-zonal and bi-communal formula. But no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
