<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Showing Interest in China's Chemicals Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- At the International Chemical
Industry Fair '98, the South Africa Trade and Economic Delegation
is made up of representatives of 14 major chemical businesses and
some small companies.
</P>
<P>
China and South Africa established diplomatic relations in
December 1997, and according to Yusuf Adam, South Africa's
Economic Counsellor to China, this is the first South African
delegation to attend a specialized exhibition in China.
</P>
<P>
He says they hope this exhibition can kick-off their business
opening in China. The companies involved are in manufacturing and
research in organic and inorganic chemicals, and fine and
daily-use chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
Sasol Limited and Agrocrop Corp., two large South African
chemical companies, are already doing business in China, Adam
says, and the products are exported to other markets.
</P>
<P>
An official with China's State Bureau of Petroleum and Chemical
Industry who is in charge of the exhibition says that there is
cooperation potential in imports and exports of chemical products
and machinery for chemical machinery, and in technology transfers
from South Africa to China.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries in 1997 was worth 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars, 18 percent more than in 1996. The figure this year
is estimated at 1.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Adam says, trade is featured by low-grade,
low-technology goods and products with a low added value, but the
advanced technology of South African companies will probably help
bring up the level of bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The Polifin Company, a subsidiary of Sasol, specializes in
making plastics out of coal and related chemicals and industry
analysts say this technology is valuable to China, the world's
largest producer of coal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
