<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Firmer Ahead of Greenspan's Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
stacked on more than 1.5 percent Wednesday, with the upcoming
expiry of September options and speculation on what U.S. Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan might say about interest rates
overnight, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index rose 39.2 points to close at
2573.6, after reaching an intra-day peak of 2581.6.
</P>
<P>
"Undoubtedly the expiry of September options drove buyers into
the market to cover their short position," said Pembroke Josephson
Wright client adviser Richard Scott.
</P>
<P>
Nevitts client adviser Steve Mayne said the market was also up
on speculation about what Greenspan might say about interest rates
when he appears before a congressional committee overnight.
</P>
<P>
Mayne said the local bourse was also probably helped by the
weaker Australian dollar, which fell to 57.73 U.S. cents, down
from 58.43 cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian equities market, the all industrials index
jumped 62.1 points to 4517.1, while the all resources index firmed
22.0 to 1006.7.
</P>
<P>
Corporate activity centered on insurance group FAI Insurances
and cable maker Metal Manufactures, with shares in both companies
soaring on the back of well-founded takeover speculation.
</P>
<P>
FAI soared 19 cents as the stock topped the turnover table with
50.2 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the industrial sector, banking stocks were among
the major blue-chip movers, with the sub-index surging 82.8 points
to 5533.4.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank stacked on six cents, while ANZ gained
14, Westpac picked up 11 and Commonwealth firmed four.
</P>
<P>
Telstra instalment receipts firmed five, while Woolworths rose
11 and fellow retailer Coles Myer gained six.
</P>
<P>
Among the oil and gas players, Woodside Petroleum rose 25
cents, while Santos gained 18. Aluminum giant Comalco rose 37
cents, or 6.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 15.7 points to 1039.1, despite a softening
in the price of the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney was 287.55 U.S.
dollars an ounce, down from a close of 289.05 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 444.87 million shares traded for 1.087
billion Australian dollars (630.46 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 637 to 423, and 383
stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
