<HEADLINE> Macao January-July External Trade Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Macao's exports and imports
went down in the first seven months of this year, according to
figures released Wednesday by the Macao Census and Statistics
Department.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, Macao's export volume was 9.4 billion
patacas (1.175 billion U.S. dollars), down 2.3 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Its import volume during that period stood at 9 billion patacas
(1.125 billion dollars), which dropped 8.1 percent compared with
that in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade surplus in the seven months surged by
329.8 percent over the same period last year, according to the
statistics.
</P>
<P>
In July, exports and imports showed mixed results. Exports
increased 3 percent while imports dropped 8.2 percent, resulting
in a trade surplus of 534 million patacas (66.75 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of the year, exports to Macao's
two leading markets, the United States and the European Union,
accounted for 77.2 percent of the total. The imports from China's
mainland and Hong Kong made up 55 percent of the total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
