<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Use French Satellite Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China plans to use data from
France's Spot Image satellite, one of the two most popular
resource satellites in the world, for its economic expansion and
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Spot Image Corporation Ltd, which was formed by the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and France's Spot Image
Corporation, made the announcement here today. The joint venture
will handle sales of data obtained from the French satellite at
CAS's Remote Sensing Satellite Ground Station.
</P>
<P>
Data from the French satellite will be used for China's urban
planning, disaster reduction, agriculture, forestry
development, military affairs, telecommunications, and mapping,
sources say.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is known for its accuracy and wave band and can
clearly pick out something as small as a brook or a small plot of
ground, explains Pan Xizhe, director of the China Remote Sensing
Satellite Ground Station.
</P>
<P>
A Spot-4 satellite was put up this past March. By 2010, two
Spot Image satellites will be in service.
</P>
<P>
A majority of remote sensing ground stations around the world
use either the U.S. Land satellite ot the French Spot Image
satellite. China began to use the Land satellite in 1986. But,
because of economic growth, the country is in bad need of the Spot
Image satellite data, Pan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
