<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Looking To Use Geothermal Energy Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China is paying close
attention to geothermal energy resources and plans to build
medium-sized geothermal power stations in the southwestern part of
the country, according to a senior State Development Planning
Commission official.
</P>
<P>
He says that these power stations will be built in Tibet and
western parts of Yunnan and Sichuan provinces by the year 2020 and
that priority will be given to geothermal resources with reservoir
temperatures above 200 degrees centigrade in Tibet's Yangbajing.
</P>
<P>
The country will build lesser power stations in Ruili in the
western part of Yunnan province and study geothermal resources in
Tengchong in Yunnan and the western part of Sichuan province by
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The official says that 3,000 hot spring sites have been
discovered, about 2,200 of which have temperatures above 25
degrees centigrade. China's high-temperature resources are mainly
in Tibet, Yunnan and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China has a long history of using geothermal energy, but
large-scale exploration began only 20 years ago. Geothermal energy
has been used in various sectors of industry and agriculture, and
for greenhouses and heating, the official says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rises Sharply in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's consumer
inflation continued to rise in August, from 6.6 percent in July
to 7.6 percent, Statistics South Africa said.
</P>
<P>
This was largely due to the hike in mortgage rates in July and
August, which followed the increase in the central bank's lending
rates in a bid to save the country's plummeting currency, Rand,
Business Day paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks raised their home loan rates to around 24
percent in late August, compared with below 17 percent in late
May when speculators began attacks on the South African financial
market.
</P>
<P>
The August leap is the second straight sharp rise in consumer
inflation in the country. The inflation rate hovered between
five and 5.4 percent from February to June, and then jumped to
6.6 percent in July due to the financial upheaval.
</P>
<P>
The latest rise was broadly in line with economists'
expectations and largely reflected the combination of increases
in fuel prices and interest rates, both the result of the Rand
fallout.
</P>
<P>
Core inflation, which excludes mortgage rates, certain fresh
and frozen foods and value added tax, climbed 7.6 percent year on
year in August, or 0.6 percent month on month, as compared with
7.2 percent and 0.7 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Economists said they were confident that core inflation would
remain in single digits and the pressure from the Rand's weakness
would be limited, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Month on month, the overall consumer price index rose 1.1
percent, of which housing costs contributed 0.8 of a percentage
point. But food prices recorded a month-on-month fall of 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the effects of market turmoil and the weak
Rand would be felt well into next year, with inflation peaking
around Easter, at just below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The onerous interest rates and the failure so far of the Rand
to show a sustained rally would probably combine with imported
inflation - rising costs of imports because of the weak exchange
rate - to ensure prices would continue climbing, they said.
</P>
<P>
But they also foresaw a drop in inflation next year once the
Rand stabilizes. The rate could fall to below four percent by
late next year, some economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's Economic Restructuring  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China's economic
restructuring of the past 20 years has had some clear results with
a coordinated industrial structure and optimization and escalation.
</P>
<P>
A study by the State Statistical Bureau (SSB) on the structural
changes of three industries released today says that improvements
in the country's economic set-up are largely attributable to the
government's placing priority on light industry, imports of
durable consumer goods, basic industry and infrastructure, and
tertiary industry development.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1997, China's economy and all industries had
fairly rapid development. The GDP grew 9.8 percent on average
annually, with added value of primary industry growing at 5
percent, secondary and tertiary industries by 11.9 percent and
10.6 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that structural changes in the three industries
are basically in accordance with international development rules,
with the proportion of primary industry declining and secondary
and tertiary industries growing. Changes in industrial structure
since the reform and opening-up began in the late 1970s indicate
that the three industries have more proportional representation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's Economic Restructuring  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, the relations between the public and private
economy has been adjusted and improved by encouraging private and
other non-public economies. Public ownership as a part of GDP has
declined somewhat, while private ownership has increased quickly.
</P>
<P>
Analysts give the following reasons for changes in China's
economy: a series of opening and reform policies promoting
structural readjustment; state industrial policies providing
guidance for economic readjustment; changes in domestic demand
pushing structural readjustment; changes in incomes and spending
and investment and fund-raising reforms had a new impact on
structural readjustment.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China's industrial structure has completed the
readjustment and rationalization period and started a process of
optimization and escalation, but that the country's economic
structure still has weak points. For example, the foundation of
agriculture is weak; the internal structure of industry is not
fully rational; tertiary industry has problems in volume,
irrational structure, and efficiency; repetitive projects exist in
many districts; and the existing ownership structure does not fit
the industrial structure in many ways.
</P>
<P>
To solve these problems, they suggest that the central
government increase various reforms to provide systematic
guarantees for escalation and optimization of the economic
structure.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the state should adopt new and still more active
measures to expand its opening efforts and participate in
international competition and exchanges, and proper industrial
policies should be formulated for better distribution of social
resources and coordinated development of different industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
