<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reconfirms Support for U.N. Resolutions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia has reconfirmed its
support to U.N. resolutions on Cyprus as well as negotiations to
reach a bizonal, bicommunal federation on the island.
</P>
<P>
The position was stated by Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov in a meeting Tuesday with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides on the sidelines of the 53rd U.N. General Assembly in
New York, Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's support to U.N. resolutions and the two High
Level Agreements as well as its support to the present basis
of the negotiations for a bizonal, bicommunal federation were
reconfirmed," CNA quoted government spokesman Christos Stylianides
as saying at a press briefing in New York.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said President Clerides and Ivanov had discussed
latest developments of the Cyprus problem, in the presence of
Russian Foreign Ministry Cyprus Envoy, Vladimir Tchizov, and
other officials.
</P>
<P>
The two High Level Agreements, reached between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides in 1977 and 1979, stipulate for the
establishment of a bizonal, bicommunal federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Last month Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash put forward
a proposal for a confederation of two equal states in Cyprus,
which has been rejected by the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the possibility of a debate of the Cyprus
problem at the U.N. Security Council was also discussed at the
meeting, but he refrained from disclosing Russia's position.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a controversial deal with Russia last year to
buy surface-to-air S-300 missile system to boost its air
defense.
</P>
<P>
The deal has triggered threats from Turkey which vowed to
strike the missiles if they are deployed on the island,
scheduled for November this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", recognized only
by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
