<HEADLINE> Iran Expects Peaceful Solution to Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said here on Wednesday that Iran expects a peaceful
solution to the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon return from the 53rd United Nations General
Assembly, Khatami said that Tehran does not welcome war, the
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that Afghan issue was one of the most important issues
discussed at the 53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly and the
U.N. would send a team to Afghanistan to probe into the crimes
committed by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team would also investigate the issue of killing eight
Iranian diplomats and a reporter by the Taliban forces in Mazari
Sharif, northern Afghanistan, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
However, he reiterated that Iran reserves the right to defend
itself, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The moderate Iranian government stressed to resort to peaceful
means to solve the issue of the killing of Iranians, despite of
the popular demand for military action to take revenge on the
Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian army and the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps
have deployed over 270,000 troops along the country's
850-kilometer eastern border with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian army has announced to launch a grand maneuver
with 200,000 troops in an area of 5,000 square kilometers in
the border area in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Terming his visit to the U.N. as "fruitful," Khatami also said
that Iran, with a logic and principled system, has new words for
the world, the Islamic world in particular.
</P>
<P>
He referred to his speech on the dialogue among civilizations
at the U.N. General Assembly held in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed satisfaction with the common view at the
General Assembly on establishing just peace in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
