<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Woman Could Win Oldest People Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan woman, who is now
registered as 125 years old, is fit to win oldest people title in
the world, the Daily Nation newspaper revealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-independence (1963) census, Naomi Kakuvi Muamba was
assessed to have been born in 1873, and this puts her age at 125
now, challenging the edict that Jeanne Calment, the French woman
who died at the age of 122, to be the oldest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Never mind the variance that's probable in such age
assessments, Naomi's own history leaves no doubt that she has
lived that long, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As a grand matriarch, Naomi has seen four generations spawned
in her lifetime, with a number of 284 children in the lineage.
She lives in a farm over 200 kilometers east of capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Skin shrunken, eyes sunken, and the mouth drooling, Naomi's
story dates back to those olden days when she and her brothers
went to graze in the fields, and when people trod for miles to
get soda ash, and then traded this for food or beer.
</P>
<P>
She remembered the raids by the neighboring Maasai people, in
whose hands two of her brothers met their deaths. She belongs to
the Kamba tribe.
</P>
<P>
By the time she was ripe for marriage, both her parents were
dead, and her elder brother married her off to Muamba, a wealthy
herdsman who took her as his third wife.
</P>
<P>
It was in 1892 that she gave birth to her first child,
Munyw'ovii, who died in 1993 at the age of 99.
</P>
<P>
All in all, she has eight children, and the last born, Mbesa,
was born in 1930. She also recalled that she lost another child
while in its infancy, but cannot remember its name.
</P>
<P>
Her children gave her 48 grandchildren, who in turn gave birth
to 179 great grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
Naomi enjoys relatively good health, though she hit her toe
while supporting herself out of bed two months ago.
</P>
<P>
The toe is now healing, although it had developed into a big
wound, which occupied the better part of her thoughts.
</P>
<P>
On other occasions, she gets incoherent, and keeps repeating
what she said before.
</P>
<P>
These are the complications that come with old age, especially
when her only surviving brother, Peter Kitemu, died in 1993, and
her grandson Titus Kaunda Mutiso, who was very close to her,
passed away.
</P>
<P>
Naomi quitted active life about 35 years ago, and the last
time she traveled over long distance was in 1985 when she visited
daughter Lois.
</P>
<P>
She used to eat pawpaws, but now only consumes bananas, not to
mention that she also takes milk and eats pumpkins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
