<HEADLINE> Iranian News Agency Calls for Release of Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran's official news agency
IRNA called Wednesday for "immediate and unconditional release" of
two of its staff detained by a Tehran court.
</P>
<P>
IRNA editorial board held an emergency meeting early in the
day, demanding job security, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
IRNA Deputy Managing Director Mohammad Reza Sadeq and Social
Desk Chief Editor Ali Reza Khosrawi were summoned to the court on
Tuesday and detained after five hours of questioning.
</P>
<P>
The detention followed a complaint lodged against IRNA by head
of the Foundation for the Oppressed and Disabled Mohsen Rafiqdoust
for its report about an assassination attempt on him.
</P>
<P>
An unknown gunman opened fire on Tuesday at Rafiqdoust, who
escaped the killing.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times daily reported on Wednesday that IRNA said the
assailant was a disgruntled war disabled who was not satisfied
with the performance of Rafiqdoust, whose foundation is
responsible for securing the life of the war disabled.
</P>
<P>
Rafiqdoust blamed IRNA for revealing the identity of the
assailant.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in 10 days that reporters were arrested
in Iran after the Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei warned
against a tendency of "freedom abuse."
</P>
<P>
Last week, the moderate Tous daily was banned and some of its
editors were detained by the conservative judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary's moves have sparked harsh reaction of the
Iranian media, which criticize it for misinterpreting and abusing
Khamenei's speech.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the judiciary's measures are contrary to the
spirit of the leader's warning," Tehran Times quoted an analyst as
saying. 
</P>
