<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Increase on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Oil prices closed higher
Tuesday on the U.S. market amid hurricane disrupting operations in
the U.S. Virgin Islands and the Gulf of Mexico, according to
market sources.
</P>
<P>
At the New York Mercantile Exchange, crude oil for October
delivery closed 18 cents higher at 15.67 U.S. dollar a
barrel. October gasoline ended 0.75 cent a gallon higher at 46.22
cents and October heating oil 0.17 cent a gallon higher at 42.16
cents.
</P>
<P>
Market sources pointed out that Hurricane Georges, which closed
oil refineries in the Caribbean and are threatening the operations
in the U.S. Virgin Islands and the Dominican Republic, had
contributed to the latest increase of oil prices.
</P>
<P>
As the Hurricane Georges headed toward the Dominican Republic
and Haiti, they said, two new tropical storms, Ivan and Jeanne,
loomed farther out in the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, forecasters said the storms were still too far off
to affect the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that several weeks of hurricanes and tropical
storms have interrupted offshore oil production and Gulf tanker
loading schedules, leading to drawdowns in U.S. oil stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
