<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 276 Die of Dengue in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 276 people died of
dengue fever in the Philippines in the first nine months of 1998,
while the number of dengue cases reached a 10-year high of more
than 15,000 during the period, health authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health said that with dengue fever yet to
peak in October, the reported dengue cases nationwide from January
to September totaled 15,650, much higher than the 1996 figure of
14,648.
</P>
<P>
However, the department declared that the number of dengue hot
spot areas in the country has been reduced to two from a high of
18 early this month.
</P>
<P>
An area is declared as "hot spot" when an increasing number of
cases is observed for at least two consecutive weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Dengue cases continue to rise but they are sporadic," Health
Secretary Alberto Romualdez explained.
</P>
<P>
The health chief said that not all dengue fever cases reported
were from outbreak sites.
</P>
<P>
Dengue outbreaks are still going on in Dumaguete City in
southern Negros Oriental province and in the towns of San Antonio
and Jaen in central Nueva Ecija province.
</P>
<P>
Dengue control lies in the hands of the people, Romualdez said,
stressing that the key to dengue control is the elimination of
mosquito breeding sites.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is transmitted only by the bite of the infected female
Aedes mosquitoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
