<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Sign CTBT Only After Conditions Met: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said Wednesday that India would sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) as a nuclear weapon power
only its conditions were fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen on board a special aircraft on his way to
New York to participate in the 53rd session of the United Nations
General Assembly, Vajpayee said that India was in no hurry to sign
the treaty without getting adequate assurances.
</P>
<P>
He, however, did not give any details about India's conditions
for the signing of CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Officials accompanying the prime minister explained that New
Delhi was primarily pressing for a minimum nuclear deterrent and
there no hurdles in dual use technology to formally adhere to the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether India was close to signing the treaty,
Vajpayee said that talks are still going on.
</P>
<P>
India has firmly rejected artificial deadlines the United
States has been trying to set for New Delhi to sign CTBT by
attempting to link it to President Bill Clinton's visit to India,
Press Trust of India (PTI) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Disapproval of such attempts (to sign the treaty) was expressed
by the prime minister's special emissary, Jaswant Singh, when he
met some of the representatives of Indian community in Washington
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jaswant Singh was in Washington for his fifth round of talks
with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and they
decided to meet again in November.
</P>
<P>
India and the U.S. started their talks on CTBT on June 11
following India's nuclear tests in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Jaswant Singh was reported to have told Strobe Talbott that
India would sign CTBT when it is convinced that it is in New Delhi
security interest, not because Clinton will or will not come to
India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
