<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Shift Work Affects Blood Pressure Cycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 22 (Xinhua) -- People who work evening
and night shift are less likely than day shift workers to show a
"dip" in blood pressure levels while asleep, according to a study
published in the latest issue of American journal Hypertension.
</P>
<P>
Fumiyasu Yamasaki and his colleagues in the New York
Hospital-Cornell Medical Center studied a group of 93 nurses,
including 58 day shift workers and 35 evening and night shift
workers.
</P>
<P>
The researchers monitored the nurses' blood pressure over a
24-hour period and asked them to keep "sleep diaries."
</P>
<P>
They found that late shift workers had higher systolic blood
pressure and saw a smaller dip in systolic blood pressure during
sleep than the day workers.
</P>
<P>
The night and evening shift workers were more than 6 times as
likely to be "nondippers" -- to show a negligible dip in blood
pressure during sleep -- as the day shift workers, the researchers
reported in the study.
</P>
<P>
Blood pressure levels usually dip somewhat during sleep, but
working the late shift seems to disrupt this natural diurnal
cycle, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a group of researchers led by Allan
Geliebter with Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York reported that
people who work the late shift may be more likely to pile on the
pounds than their day-working counterparts.
</P>
<P>
In the study, the researchers asked 85 hospital employees, who
had worked their current day shift, evening shift and night shift
respectively for an average of 8.6 years, about weight changes as
well as changes in food intake, exercise and sleep.
</P>
<P>
The evening and night shift workers reported that they gained
an average of 4.3 kilograms while working the late shift. In
comparison, day workers said they gained only 0.9 kilograms during
the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
