<HEADLINE> Paris Club Agrees to Reschedule Indonesian Govt Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen creditor countries
have agreed to extend by 20 years the repayment of 4.2 billion
U.S. dollars in Indonesian sovereign debts, a minister told
reporters here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the Paris Club meeting which
began in Paris Tuesday, Finance Minister Bambang Soebianto said.
</P>
<P>
After reporting to President B.J. Habibie here, Bambang told
reporters that Habibie was glad over the development.
</P>
<P>
The debts that were rescheduled were those signed before July
1, 1997 whose principals are scheduled to be repaid from August 6,
1998 until March 31, 2000. These include export credits amounting
to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Bank Indonesia Sjahril Sabirin told reporters that
the rescheduling of the country's sovereign debts will ease the
government's burden and reduce the pressure on the state budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
