<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US "Science" Magazine Has More Readers in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The American journal
"Science," one of the most authoritative academic periodicals in
the world, is attracting more readers in China.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year more than 24,000
Chinese have visited the "Science" website on the Internet, said
Ellis Rubinstein, editor in chief of the magazine, who is here
attending a celebration of the 40th anniversary of the China
Association for Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
"There were only 13 subscribers to "Science" in China 10 years
ago. But now there are about 800 subscribers of the printed
edition in the mainland and Hong Kong," said Rubinstein. "This is
a good number compared with other countries."
</P>
<P>
Since "Science" became available on the Internet in Beijing in
January, Chinese researchers and students have been accessing the
lastest editions of the journal on both the China Science and
Technology Network and the China Education and Research Network.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein said he hopes the Chinese government will
continue to support the development of the Internet, through which
Chinese scientists may obtain instant information on the World
Wide Web and thereby enjoy fair competition with their foreign
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"Science" is published weekly and enjoys a high reputation in
international scientific research circles, especially for its
articles on biology and medical science.
</P>
<P>
Although more and more Chinese read "Science," the number of
Chinese scientists who publish their papers in the magazine remains
very small.
</P>
<P>
Only two or three papers written by Chinese scientists are
published in the magazine every year, along with about ten papers
written jointly by scientists of China and other countries,
according to Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, it's difficult for scientists anywhere in the world
to have their papers published in our magazine. Lots of scientists
submit their very best papers to us, but only one in eight or one
in ten can be accepted," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But there's no nation we expect more papers from than China in
the long run because of its devotion to science. So I expect
very large changes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
