<HEADLINE> China Using Steel Chambers To Develop Bohai Gulf Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China has started using steel
chambers to build drilling and storage platforms in offshore oil
operations at the Jinzhou 9-3 oilfield in the Bohai Gulf in the
North.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, president of the China Offshore Oil
Bohai Corporation (COOBC), this is the first time this kind of
technology has been used.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou 9-3 is located in icy seas 20 km from the city of
Jinzhou in Liaoning Province in northeast China. It has proven oil
reserves of more than 30 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Lin says that oil development by conventional methods in there
would be very costly and very difficult to recover the
investment. So, after eight years of studies, petroleum engineers
decided to put steel chambers down in the water instead of the
conventional oil exploration methods for efficiency and safety.
</P>
<P>
Round containers 13.8 m. tall and 38 m. in diameter are being
used.
</P>
<P>
This oilfield now has 27 producing wells, 26 water filling
wells, and one natural gas well, and a designed annual oil
capacity of a million tons. It will go into production in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
