<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Economic Record Fails to Win Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Wednesday called on voters to support his tax plan as
his sound economic record and his strategy of centering the
current election campaign on economic management has failed to
gain him a decisive edge in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister spent one hour Wednesday in Sydney on the
nationally syndicated John Laws radio program selling his
controversial tax plan, calling on listeners to look at the
long-term benefit the plan will provide the nation.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came as the latest opinion poll Newspoll found the
ruling Liberal Party of Australia and National Party coalition has
yet to work harder to sell their tax plan to get a clear lead in
the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of the latest survey, published
Tuesday by the nation's leading national newspaper The Australian,
the primary vote for the Australian Labor Party, the opposition,
is up one percentage point in a week to 43 percent while the
coalition's is steady on 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the day he announced the October 3 poll date, the prime
minister said the election campaign would be fought on economic
management, citing his government's sound economic management
record as well as the government's ambitious plan to reform the
nation's 60-year-old taxation system in a bid to build an
economically secure and "stronger Australia".
</P>
<P>
With the nation's jobless rate as high as 8.1 percent and its
failures in industrial reforms and controlling rising racism, the
nation's economic management remains the government's only bright
spot.
</P>
<P>
The government's economic achievements include turning budget
deficit left over by the previous Labor government in 1996 into an
expected surplus in this financial year, and delivering the lowest
interest rates in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Savage budget cuts in welfare, education and government
services by the Howard government since 1996 have helped it turn 6
billion U.S. dollar budget deficit into an estimated surplus of
1.5 billion U.S. dollars for the first time in almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
The deep cuts are certain to cost the coalition many votes, for
example, from students, but the government has gained much support
from those benefiting from lower home-loan interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The home-loan interest rates have been brought to their lowest
levels since 1970 due to cuts in interest rate reduction, which
represents a saving of about 185 U.S. dollars a month for a family
with a 58,000 U.S. dollar mortgage.
</P>
<P>
The latest official gross domestic product statistics also gave
the government high scores, showing the nation's economy grew at
an unexpected 3.9 percent during the past financial year ending
June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, to the nation's 12 million voters, what matters most
is whether they would be better off or worse off under the
coalition's tax plan, which was released two weeks before the
campaign began on August 30.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, a 10 percent goods and services tax would be
imposed, which would cut business costs by 6 billion U.S. dollars
each year but inflation would go up by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the coalition centering the election campaign on its
economic competence, the opposition party has been focusing its
attack on the negative impact of the tax reform, saying the plan
is unfair to middle class and low income earners.
</P>
<P>
But with the polling date just 10 days away, the two sides have
not yet achieved substantial advantage in their publicity war
against each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
