<HEADLINE> Chinese Enjoying Better Standard of Living (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The standard of living of the
Chinese has improved along with the economic development of the
past 20 years, according to the State Statistics Bureau, and
people are now earning more in more different ways.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1997 per capita disposable income of
urban Chinese was 5,160 yuan, 3.1 times that of 1978, and per
capita net income of rural residents was 2,090 yuan, 4.4 times
1978's figure.
</P>
<P>
Spending habits have also changed, with Chinese now spending
more on entertainment and services, instead of just food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
Sales of grains and non-staple foods have increased while
coarse food grain sales have decreased and people now spend more
on dress and clothes are not just something to keep a person warm
any more.
</P>
<P>
Chinese also have more durable goods now and their living
conditions have improved a great deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enjoying Better Standard of Living (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1997, the per capita floor space of urban residents was 8.8
sq.m., compared with 1978's 3.6 sq.m. and that in rural areas was
22 sq.m., up from 8.1 sq.m.
</P>
<P>
Chinese now have better transportation facilities, medical
care, and pension system.
</P>
<P>
World Bank statistics show that, although China's per capita
GDP is still similar to that of low-income countries, other
indices of living standards have reached average levels.
</P>
<P>
China has made agriculture the basis for economic development
and has tried to develop the service industry, the bureau says,
and the country has adopted an income distribution system that
encourages production.
</P>
<P>
The bureau says that the government still needs to pay closer
attention to some problems like the plight of the poor, the
widening income gap, and the pattern of consumer spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
