<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't to Strengthen Aviation Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
planning to craft effective ways to support the operations of
other remaining commercial airlines before they suffer the
ill-fate of the debt-ridden Philippine Airlines (PAL).
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed Wednesday by Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu who expressed doubts that the operations of PAL will be
nursed back to life considering its huge obligations which are
more than the selling value of its assets.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the focus of Wednesday's discussion by
members of a special task force created by President Joseph
Estrada is to ask other airline management to upgrade their
capacities in order to serve the interests of the riding public.
</P>
<P>
Instead of focusing attention on how to revive PAL, he said, it
is still better for the government to discuss matters that would
be beneficial to other airline companies to improve their
operations.
</P>
<P>
He discounted earlier reports that the government will still
have to pump in some 1.5 billion pesos (34 million U.S. dollars)
in fresh funds to help PAL stand on its feet again due to the
failure of the PAL management and labor to agree on a rebuilding
plan for PAL.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the on-going row could not be settled unless
the unions will reasonably cooperate with what the PAL management
wants.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management declared last week it will shut down the
airline at midnight Wednesday after the unions refused to accept a
co-ownership plan in exchange for a 10-year suspension of their
collective bargaining agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
