<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment to Go Down in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment
(FDI) in most parts of Southeast Asia is seen to taper off in the
remaining months of this year, contrary to the substantial
increases experienced by the regional economies in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development in its assessment report available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the FDI flows into the countries stricken
by the financial crisis since July 1997 were found to be resilient
despite the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Inflows last year to the five Asian economies most affected by
the financial crisis -- Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, the
Republic of Korea and Thailand -- remained at a level almost
unchanged from that in 1996," the report said.
</P>
<P>
This was different from the bank lending and portfolio equity
investment which fell sharply in 1997, it added.
</P>
<P>
But the U.N. body said that foreign direct investment inflows
to these affected countries may not return to its 1996-1997
levels.
</P>
<P>
It said a number of factors had influenced investment inflows
as well as the operations of transnational corporations in the
affected countries.
</P>
<P>
One of the factors enumerated in the report is that dollar
costs for foreign investors in expanding their investments have
decreased because asset prices fell considerably.
</P>
<P>
Another visible consequence of the financial crisis is the
reduced domestic demand and slower economic growth that could lead
to the canceling, scaling down or postponement of FDI in these
affected countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
