<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 092359 Zambian Vice-President Warns Gay Lobbists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Vice-President
Christon Tembo has warned that gay lobbyists and other champions
of acts against the order of nature would, from Wednesday, be
arrested and charged with conspiring to commit criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
When clarifying the Zambian government's stand on the status
of gays and champions of their cause in parliament Tuesday, Tembo
said the government policy was very clearly reflected by
legislation and in particular the country's Penal Code which
criminalized acts against the order of nature and morality,
government-owned Times of Zambia said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If anybody promotes gay rights after this statement the law
will take its course. We need to protect public morality. Human
rights do not operate in a vacuum," said the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's Penal Code provides that anyone who has carnal
knowledge of any person against the order of nature or permits a
male person to have unnatural carnal knowledge of him or her is
guilty of a felony.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for imprisonment of up to five years if
convicted of practising homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, a group called the Lesbians, Gays and
Transgender Persons Association (LEGATRA) has emerged in Zambia
and is trying to register with the Registrar of Societies.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Zulu, a champion of the group and president of the
Zambia Independent Monitoring Team (ZIMT), a non-governmental
organization, once said there were 500,000 gays or lesbians
throughout the country and last week, he claimed that some of the
senior government officials and parliament members were also gays
and they even had registered with the LEGATRA.
</P>
<P>
However, Tembo denied this claim and said the gay organization
would never be registered because the country's Societies Act
gave the Registrar of Societies the obligation to refuse
registration of any society whose terms of constitution were
repugnant or inconsistent with the law.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to all Zambians, especially the young, that
it was not to be modern to champion new and ugly causes such as
homosexuality as this was against the Zambian norms and values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
