<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows not to Repeat Sang Lan Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Shi Ting
</P>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- For every Chinese gymnast,
the 1998 China Cup International must be the safest tournament
they have ever competed in, both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
A protection cushion will be placed close to the apparatus for
the gymnasts to land, and coaches will be allowed to step forward
to serve protection on every setting.
</P>
<P>
And even more, if unfortunately and to the worst, a Chinese
gymnast gets hurt in the China Cup, which opens tomorrow, he/she
could obtain a guaranteed insurance as high as 100,000 yuans
(some 12,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"It sounds good and gives us a psychological boost," Chinese
top woman gymnast Liu Xuan said, "We do not have to worry about
getting wounded any more."
</P>
<P>
These are the latest measures being taken by the Chinese
Gymnastics Association (CGA) to prevent the Sang Lan tragedy from
repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
Sang Lan, a 17-year-old national vaulting champion, accidently
broke her neck in a practice vault at the Goodwill Games this
July, and still lay paralyzed in a hospital in the United
States. As she was the only athlete suffering major injury at
the Games, the tournament's insurance money totalling 20 million
US dollars will all be contributed to her recovery.
</P>
<P>
As CGA vice president Zhang Jian revealed, to go on with its
efforts to establish a safe environment for the Chinese athletes,
the Chinese State Sports General Administration will have applied
insurance for 1,400 athletes by the end of the year, including 70
gymnasts. The highest insurance will be up to 300,000 yuans
(36,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, Zhang urged every gymnast to develop a high sense
of safety awareness in both training and competition. Thus,
gymnasts will be "attentive, more in tune with what is going on
around them and more apt to avoid mistakes and injuries", he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, CGA also complained to the International
Gymnastics Federation (FIG), suggesting that FIG should promote
artistry, execution and originality in gymnastics instead of
focusing too much on difficulty as in the new Code of Points.
</P>
<P>
Although women's head coach Lu Shanzhen had earlier said
"enthusiasm for training in China is not as high as it was
before", most Chinese gymnasts claimed they had not been affected
much by Sang Lang's brutal accident.
</P>
<P>
"Everything is going on as usual," World Cup uneven bars
champion Bi Wenjing said, "We are not afraid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0187 </DOCNO>
