<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Back U.S. Trade-Not-Aid Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- African countries have been
urged to support the U.S. trade-not-aid policy which is designed
to encourage increased trade and investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going fifth African Stock Exchanges
International Conference held in Lusaka Tuesday, Erastus Mwencha,
secretary general of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA), said the policy should be supported for the good
of Africa, Times of Zambia reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 14 members of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) rejected at an annual summit the proposed U.S.
trade-not-aid policy to Africa, saying the region still needs
development aid.
</P>
<P>
There were some concerns that the U.S. policy to Africa still
had inadequacies, said Mwencha, but it was clear that several
countries were bound to benefit from the initiative.
</P>
<P>
There was need to endorse the policy by Africa as a continent
and later to make necessary amendments where there were
inadequacies, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha, in the same presentation, differed with the stand
taken by South Africa who have called for a rejection of the U.S.
trade initiative.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa is a little selfish in making that stand because
they already have an existing bilateral agreement with the
U.S.A.," he said.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that while it was true that not all clauses
of the proposed act were acceptable, the little benefit that it
yielded would trickle down to other countries on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. policy initiated by President Bill Clinton early
this year, said the secretary general, would allow for an
expansion of sub-Saharan opportunities to trade with the U.S. and
create numerous job opportunities in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
