<HEADLINE> Islamic Countries Coordinate Stances on Issues: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) Ezzidine Laraki said
on Wednesday that Islamic countries are coordinating stances on
issues raised at the ongoing 53rd United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Egypt's Sawt al Arab (Voice of
Arab) radio from Moroccan capital Rabat before he flew to New
York, Laraki said that Islamic countries' foreign ministers will
hold a meeting late this week for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The OIC is concerned with the Middle East peace process, the
Afghan situations and other regional and international issues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated OIC's support for the establishment of a
Palestinian state, saying the international community should halt
Israel's attempts to judaize the holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has announced that an
independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital will
be declared next May when the Oslo Accord signed with Israel in
1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
Referring to OIC's role in helping settle the disputes between
Iran and the Afghan Taliban group, Laraki said the organization
believes in the need to solve the problem peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Angered by Taliban's killing of eight Iranian diplomats and a
reporter in northern Afghanistan last month, Iran has threatened
to take military actions against the group.
</P>
<P>
The OIC chief said that his organization is arranging for an
international conference on integration of cultures to assert the
role of Islam in serving human development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
