<HEADLINE> China Cup Gymnastics Opens Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 China Cup
International Gymnastics Tournament is to kick off tomorrow here
in the Tianjin Sports Center, the stadium to host next year's
world championships.
</P>
<P>
A total of 194 gymnasts from 17 countries will participate in
the annual event which, in the viewpoint of the organizers, will
serve as a rehearsal to gain experiences in competition
organization and reception for the 1999 worlds.
</P>
<P>
The participating gymnasts are from Australia, Belarus,
Bulgaria, Canada, Denmark, DPR Korea, France, Germany, Hungary,
Japan, Norway, Romania, Sweden, Switzerland, Thailand, the United
States and host China.
</P>
<P>
"The tournament will lay sound foundations for the successful
holding of the 1999 World Gymnastics Championships," said Zhang
Faqiang, president of the Chinese Gymnastics Association.
</P>
<P>
However, the event, which spreads over two days with the team
and individual all-round competitions on September 24 and ten
apparatus finals on September 25, could hardly claim to be a
showcase of the world's best with no Russian gymnasts present and
other participating countries apparently having not dispatched
their first-string teams.
</P>
<P>
The top Chinese men's gymnast, world and World Cup champion
Zhang Jinjing who won five titles in the previous edition, is not
to show up as he was instead attending an exibition in Belgium
together with woman gymnast Meng Fei.
</P>
<P>
The host China will send three teams to the competitions:
China A, headlined by Goodwill Games pommel horse champion Huang
Xu and World Cup beam champion Liu Xuan, China B, led by World
Cup double champion in floor and bars Li Xiaopeng, and the local
Tianjin team.
</P>
<P>
The next year's worlds is scheduled on October 8-16 in
Tianjin, 120 kilometers from the capital of Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
