<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Issue Foreign Exchange Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will float foreign
exchange bonds to create an Industrial Development Fund designed
to help finance the country's industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
A cabinet meeting on economic affairs on Tuesday approved the
introduction of the bonds worth 200 million U.S. dollars, to be
sold to non-resident Bangladeshis, the English-language daily The
Financial Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fund, to be administered by a proposed "Industrial
Development Company," will be used to meet the demand for
industrial loans, Commerce and Industry Minister Tofail Ahmed
said.
</P>
<P>
"There are lots of non-resident Bangladeshis who are interested
in the investment in the country" and "introduction of the new
bonds will fulfill their interest as well as the country's need
for funds to be invested in the industrial sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bonds, to be sold by the national Sonali Bank, would be
issued "as soon as possible," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minimum value of a bond is 2,000 dollars or 1,000 British
pounds.
</P>
<P>
The five-year term dollar bonds would have an interest rate of
7.75 percent and pound bonds a rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
All the payments including interest payment or payment upon
maturity would be made in the same currency the bond was bought
and in case of immature cashing, the bond holder would not suffer
any penalty or loss, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
