<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Shanghai Residents Live Urban Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Rural residents of Shanghai,
China's leading industrial and commercial city, now live in a way
formerly enjoyed only by urbanites.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the development of several small towns
and expansion of the township areas in recent years. Shanghai has
built 209 new small towns with 1.6 million people over the
decade or so.
</P>
<P>
All these towns have electricity, water and gas and a complete
communications network. They also have automated and
program-controlled telephones, and construction of digital
telecommunications facilities and Internet services are underway.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 839 kindergartens, 894 primary schools, 271 middle
schools and 173 vocational schools are available to all children.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 cultural centers, 187 libraries, 183 cinemas, 73
stadiums, 201 broadcasting stations and 46 television relay
stations offer a broad range of cultural activities to the local
residents.
</P>
<P>
According to Shanghai officials, these towns are playing an
important role in promoting the prosperity of rural markets.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's small towns now have 296 department stores and 127
outdoor markets, and the annual average revenue for each town
stands at 23.24 million yuan (2.8 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
