<HEADLINE> Gunfire Continues in Maseru, Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- There was gunfire in
the Lesotho capital of Maseru Wednesday morning, apparently
showing intervention troops from South Africa had not yet put
situation in the city under full control.
</P>
<P>
South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) said gunfire was
heard in Maseru again and people were running on the streets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more soliders from the Southern African Development
Community (SADC)'s intervention force have crossed the border
into Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The additional troops were mainly from Botswana, South African
immigration service official Naas Kotze was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said Tuesday night at least 200 soldiers from
Botswana were due to cross into Lesotho Wednesday morning to join
their 600 South African counterparts.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known how many SADC soldiers have been
involved in the military intervention altogether.
</P>
<P>
It is also not yet known if Zimbabwe has sent its troops to
Lesotho to help restore stability in the mountain kingdom.
Zimbabwe is one of the three SADC nations that was involved in an
investigation into the Lesotho May 23 general elections, which,
opposition parties in the country said, was rigged.
</P>
<P>
The intervention force, acting under the auspices of the SADC
and at the request of the Lesotho government, entered Lesotho
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
An unconfirmed total of 30 people died in subsequent clashes.
Five of the casualties were South African soldiers. SABC
Television reported that 17 members of the Lesotho Defense Force
were killed as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
