<HEADLINE> Autopsy Continues on Flo-Jo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An autopsy continued
today on three Olympic gold medalist Florence Griffith Joyner,
who died suddenly Monday in her home.
</P>
<P>
There was no estimate for when the autopsy would be completed,
said Lt. Hector Rivera, spokesman for the Orange County Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
"The testing is not concluded and therefore final results are
not available," he said. "As soon as all the test information is
in and the coroner has determined the cause of death, we'll put
that out."
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner, 38, died Monday. Her husband called
authorities after finding her "unresponsive and not breathing,"
Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
"She died in her sleep sometime during the night," he added.
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner was born on December 21, 1959, in Los A
ngeles. She married Al Joyner in 1987. They have a 7-year-old
daughter, Mary Ruth.
</P>
<P>
After winning three gold medals and set two world records for
the 100 and 200 meters, Griffith Joyner retired from track
following the Seoul Olympics in 1989, and she served as co-chair
of the President's Council on Physical Fitness.
</P>
<P>
Funeral arrangements were not immediately announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
