<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal City Turns Into Red-Wine Production Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The port city of
Qinhuangdao in north China's Hebei Province has become one of
China's leading dry red-wine producers, turning out 20,000
tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The city turned out 8,500 tons of red wine last year,
one-third of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Areas along a section of Great Wall near Qinhuangdao are
suitable for growing grapes due to its fertile soil, plentiful
sunshine, mild climate and appropriate rainfall.
</P>
<P>
In Changli County, one of the leading grape producers, 20,000
farmers are now engaged in growing grapes. According to the county
development plan, the vineyard area will eventually sprawl to
12,000 hectares by the year 2000 and to 46,600 hectares by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the area's annual output of red wine is expected
to reach 130,000 tons by 2000 and soar to 500,000 tons by 2010, a
county magistrate said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
