<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Elephants Killed in 40 Days in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Twenty elephants have been
killed during the past 40 days in Sri Lanka, the Wild Life
Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Department officials told Xinhua that the elephants had been
shot and died due to the lack of medical care.
</P>
<P>
Most of the elephants were males and were killed for their
tusks. The highest number of killings was recorded in Polonnaruwa
and Anuradhapura in North Central Province of the country, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that with only three specialized wild life surgeons
available in the country it is not possible to give immediate
emergency treatment to the elephants which have been shot.
</P>
<P>
Although villagers also killed elephants when their crops were
destroyed, a large number of the killing incidents are the result
of poaching, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said they have appealed to the government for necessary
measures to prevent elephant-human conflicts in the areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jute, Forest Sectors Suffer in Bangladesh Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The jute and forest industries
in Bangladesh have recorded huge losses this year due to floods
which are the worst in the century.
</P>
<P>
The jute sector alone suffered an estimated loss of 3.56
billion taka (about 75.74 million U.S. dollars), State Minister
for Jute A.K. Faizul Huq said Tuesday, The Daily Star newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the preliminary estimate has been made on the basis of
reports of crop damage and losses of public and private sector
jute mills and traders.
</P>
<P>
The devastating floods hampered production of jute, damaged the
finished goods and jute stocks in mills and godowns the machinery
and equipment of jute mills and caused a colossal trade loss
during the last two and a half months, he said.
</P>
<P>
The forest sector sustained losses amounting to 1.103 billion
taka (about 23.46 million dollars) and its rehabilitation may cost
almost the same amount of money, Forest and Environment Minister
Begum Sajeda Chowdhury said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The losses include 57.6 million taka (about 1.23 million
dollars) in damage to forests under the Forest Division, 920
million taka (about 19.57 million dollars) to rural forests and
125 million taka (about 2.7 million dollars) to nurseries.
</P>
<P>
A scheme has been taken up to assess the short- and long-term
impact on the environment. "The environmental impact assessment
will be for the first time in the country," Chowdhury was quoted
by The New Nation daily newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The study is essential considering factors like sanitation,
housing, transportation, vegetation, infrastructure, people's
response, institutional approaches and capabilities, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, diarrhea is spreading fast in the flood-hit
districts affecting more people.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 people have been reportedly attacked by the
disease with 306 of them dead in 52 flood-hit districts since
July.
</P>
<P>
Medical teams have been deployed in the districts to attend the
patients and check the spread of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
