<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Develop Technical, Vocational Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government has
decided to introduce a "Skills Development Project" to restructure
and develop the existing technical and vocational education system
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry of Vocational Training sources Wednesday,
 the project is to be funded by the Asian Development Bank and
preparation of the project plan will be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
The government of Japan has provided around 600,000 U.S.
dollars for the preparation of the project plan.
</P>
<P>
The project is targeted to change the existing training system
to suit present-day needs and the rural youth in the country will
be the main beneficiaries, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Financial support from the private sector will be mustered to
upgrade the vocational training system by setting up a special
Skills Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
Five leading training institutions have been identified as
participatory institutions for the project.
</P>
<P>
Ten priority sectors including vocational training, development
of institutional skills and skills-based training and career
guidance will gain priority in the project plan, the sources
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
