<HEADLINE> PM: Yugoslavia Feeling Internal and External Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister
Momir Bulatovic said Tuesday that Yugoslavia is not only
experiencing external pressure from major world powers, but is
also facing serious internal difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav News Agency Tanjug reported that Bulatovic made
the remark at a meeting of the Belgrade economic coalition.
</P>
<P>
He said his country continues to feel pressure from the world's
more powerful countries. The European Union has eliminated
Yugoslavia's most favored nation status, prohibited Yugoslavia's
airlines from landing in any EU countries, and suspended the
country's privileges to participate in many international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
On domestic difficulties, the prime minister said his
government has to resolve the Kosovo issue, while the political
conflict between Yugoslavia's Montenegro Republic and Yugoslavia
has actually divided the Yugoslav economic system. The Montenegro
Republic has not made a payment to the central government of
Yugoslavia in the past two months, Bulatovic said.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the difficulties, he said the Yugoslav government
will make efforts to resolve the existing political conflicts and
guarantee long-term economic stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
