policies to cope with the impact of the international financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said that foreign debts in the country remain in
manageable conditions and Mexico will strengthen its national
banking and financial systems. (Mexico-Economic Strategy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippines is planning to achieve a 5-percent
gross domestic product (GDP) growth beginning year 2000 after
taking steps to revive the economy which is facing recession due
to the current regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The plan is contained in a memorandum on economic and financial
policies reached recently between the government and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in connection with its
precautionary arrangement signed with the IMF early this year.
(Philippines-Economic Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government is reportedly considering
lifting both the import duty and value-added tax (VAT) on
automotive parts in a bid to salvage the crippled automotive
industry and the transportation sector.
</P>
<P>
The government is currently studying the possibility of
slashing the 25-percent import duty and 10-percent VAT on car
spare parts to lower their skyrocketing domestic prices, Minister
of Industry and Trade Rahardi Ramelan was quoted Wednesday by the
Jakarta Post as saying. (Indonesia-Tax-Auto Parts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States is likely to record its first
federal budget surplus in 29 years as the 1998 fiscal year is
approaching to the end, the Treasury Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
