<HEADLINE> Clinton Lawyers Criticizes Starr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers of U.S. President
Bill Clinton on Tuesday accused independent counsel Kenneth Starr
of distorting Monica Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's attorneys fired off a letter to the House Judiciary
Committee, urging members to "proceed with due caution" as they
review materials provided by Starr.
</P>
<P>
Starr's report to Congress "distorted the testimony of Ms.
Lewinsky, quoting it when it suited the OIC (Office of Independent
Counsel)'s purposes and downplaying it or ignoring it when it did
not," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The White House seized on a statement from Lewinsky's first
grand jury appearance: "I would just like to say that no one ever
asked me to lie, and I was never promised a job for my silence."
The remark seems to back up part of Clinton's story.
</P>
<P>
Presidential lawyers said that statement stands in direct
contradiction to Starr's conclusion in his impeachment report.
</P>
<P>
"The Office of Independent Counsel found room for hundreds and
hundreds of salacious details that embarrassed this country,...but
it didn't find room for one sentence from the testimony of Monica
Lewinsky," White House press secretary Mike McCurry said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a grievous wrong to the president," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Henry Hyde, a Republican and chairman of the Judiciary
Committee of the House of Representatives, told reporters that his
staff advised him "this is not so," but he said he would consider
anything the president's lawyers brought up.
</P>
<P>
Democrats also reportedly found other pieces of Lewinsky's
testimony promising to counter allegations that Clinton tried to
obstruct justice or influence witnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
