<HEADLINE> U.S. to Sell Jet Fighters Worth $5 Billion to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
sell jet fighters worth Five billion U.S. dollars to Israel, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Pentagon stressed that the "I" models of
the F-15 jets, manufactured by Boeing Co., and the F-16 C and D
models, made by Lockheed Martin, would help maintain Israel's
military edge over its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Both F-15 and F-16 would be equipped with sophisticated
electronic targeting pods and increase the Israeli Air Force's
ground-attack capabilities, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The F-15I jets would be equipped with AN/APG-70 or AN/APG-63
radars and "LANTIRN" (Low Altitude Navigation and Targeting
Infrared for Night) navigation and targeting pods used to enhance
ground-attack capabilities, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
"This proposed sale will contribute to the foreign policy and
national security of the United States by helping to improve the
security of a friendly country which has been and continues to be
an important force for political stability and economic progress in
the Middle East," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Israel already has F-15s in its inventory, but the "I" models
would represent a major step forward in both air-to-air and
ground-attack capability for the United States' closest ally in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed sale of this equipment will not affect the basic
military balance in the region," Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon announced last Wednesday that it had offered two
billion U.S. dollars in sophisticated AMRAAM (Advanced
Medium-Range Air-to-Air Missiles) and other aircraft military
missiles made by Raytheon Co. to the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., who has urged other countries not to sell weapons to
the Middle East, is the biggest salesman of weapons in the region.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the sale to Israel may be resulted from the
progress in the Palestine-Israel talks. The U.S. is trying to
persuade Israel to compromise in the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
