<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Re-Forest, Reinforce River Banks After Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China will improve
environmental management and change the mode of economic
development along its great rivers after suffering severe losses
during this summer's flooding.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State Development Planning Zeng Peiyan told a press
conference here today that in the next 20 to 30 years, China will
increase forests to 45 percent and 27 percent of the total land
area respectively in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River and
the Yellow River, the two longest rivers in the country.
</P>
<P>
Logging and timber markets in these areas will be totally
prohibited. In addition, ten million hectares of grass will be
planted in ten soil erosion control areas in central and western
China in the next ten years so that 60 percent of the land
plagued by soil erosion and desertification can be reclaimed in
these areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will stop land-fills around lakes and turn
current farm land around the lake back into the water. In the
process of establishing a number of huge flood diversion tracts in
the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze, China will move local
residents to new towns specially designed and developed to suit
local economic conditions. The central government will provide 2.6
billion yuan for building the new towns.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises destroyed by the floods will not be restored in
their former locations. Instead, the most profitable of them will
be moved to new towns or merged with other enterprises, while
those which pollute the environment or lack advanced technology
will be closed.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that in the next two years reinforcement works along
the banks of the Yangtze, Yellow and other rivers will be
completed, enabling them to withstand the highest flood levels
recorded since the founding of New China.
</P>
<P>
In combination with the bank reinforcement project, dredging of
the Yangtze and Yellow rivers will intensify, and 540 million
cubic meters of silt will be removed from the river beds in the next
two to three years.
</P>
<P>
He said China will combine post-flood reconstruction,
management of rivers and lakes and water conservation with
expansion of the domestic market and the promotion of economic
growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
