<HEADLINE> Malaysia Asks Thailand to Block Anwar Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has asked Thai
authorities to prevent the supporters of former Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim from escaping into
Thailand, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur has requested the application of strict
immigration procedures along the Malaysian-Thai border, the report
quoted border officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The request followed reports that supporters of Anwar, now
detained under the Malaysian Internal Security Act, were planning
to flee to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said on Tuesday that
Anwar had been plotting an Indonesian-style uprising. Anwar is
facing coup plot accusation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has stepped up security and immigration measures along
the border since Anwar was arrested on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia border police have been posted in the border area
around the clock while Thai marine police have stepped up sea
patrols.
</P>
<P>
But the immigration office in Sadao district, Songkhla in
southern Thailand, said it was not aware of any such request from
Malaysia. 
</P>
