<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien Outlines Canada's Electronic Commerce Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien laid out his country's electronic commerce strategy on
Tuesday, a new step in making Canada the most connected nation in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Electronic commerce refers to business conducted by means of
advanced communications and computer technologies, such as
transactions by automated banking machines, credit and debit cards,
electronic data interchange and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategy is one of 'firsts', with the goal of recreating in
cyberspace, the same expectations of trust, confidence and
reliability that now exist in everyday commerce," Chretien said at
SoftWorld'98, a business event held in St. John's, provincial capital
of Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
The 'firsts' includes having privacy legislation to protect
personal data, a policy on the use of encryption technology, and a
world-class public key infrastructure in place.
</P>
<P>
Canada will also have new consumer protection guidelines that
ensure Canadians enjoy the same protection online that they do at
the corner store, and a revenue neutral taxation regime that is
aimed at avoiding duplicated taxes.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make Canada a world leader in electronic commerce by
the year 2000," Chretien was quoted as saying by a government news
release.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the world's electronic commerce will grow to
about 337 billion U.S. dollars by the year of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Early next month, Canada is to host a ministerial-level
conference on electronic commerce of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
