<HEADLINE> Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Eight members of an
anti-government ethnic armed group laid down their arms and
surrendered to the government last week, the newspaper The New
Light of Myanmar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These members including a deputy commanding officer from the
Lahu armed group "exchanged arms for peace" with the government at
the Triangle Region Command area on September 14.
</P>
<P>
In armed opposition to the Myanmar government, the Lahu armed
group has reportedly been operating on the Myanmar-Thai border.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups in
the country have made peace with the government, leaving the Kayin
National Union, led by Bo Mya, still in opposition on the
Myanmar-Thai border although four rounds of peace talks have been
held between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The government said it still permits the turned-in armed groups
to retain their arms for "self-protection and area-defense."
</P>
