<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fiscal Revenue Sharply Higher in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China's fiscal income
increased by 11.2 percent in August, 5.4 percentage points higher
than in July, said Minister of the State Development Planning
Commission Zeng Peiyan at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Zeng noted that in the first eight months of this year,
China's fiscal revenue was 576.6 billion yuan, up 8.9 percent
compared with the same period last year while fiscal
expenditures were 561.7 billion yuan, up 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
And accounting revenue and expenditure saw a surplus of 14.9
billion yuan in the first eight months of this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that loans extended to the government by financial
institutions have been growing month to month, with the structure
of these loans improved somewhat. By the end of August, the amount of
outstanding loans totaled 8.089 trillion yuan, up 16.4 percent,
and 0.6 percentage point higher than the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The money supply has obviously been increased since last month,
he said. By the end of August, money in circulation (M0) and
narrow money (M1) increased by 8.6 percent and 10.9 percent
respectively, compared with the same period last year, and were
2 percentage points and 2.2 percentage points higher
respectively than at the end of June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
