<HEADLINE> Kuczynski Says Magnitude of L.American Crisis Exaggerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The chairman of the Latin
America Enterprise Capital company, Pedro Pablo Kuczynski, said
Tuesday that the negative effects of the world financial crisis
on Latin America have been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian-American banker told a group of businessmen that
the harshness of the crisis on the region "is based more on
perceptions than on concrete realities".
</P>
<P>
Kuczynski criticized the allegations that Latin America's
current foreign debt was considered high, "since in reality it is
lower than 1982's level", when the so-called "debt crisis"
occurred.
</P>
<P>
The 1982 debt levels of the main countries in the region
amounted to 325 billion U.S. dollars. Exports were valued at 85
billion, which supposed a relationship of four to one between both
factors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the debt level is 600 billion dollars. Exports are
valued at almost 300 billion, a ratio of two to one, the banker
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
