<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Aims for High GDP Growth Starting 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is planning to
achieve a 5-percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth beginning
year 2000 after taking steps to revive the economy which is facing
recession due to the current regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The plan is contained in a memorandum on economic and financial
policies reached recently between the government and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in connection with its
precautionary arrangement signed with the IMF early this year.
</P>
<P>
"We are aiming at a GDP growth of about 1 percent in 1998,
followed by a recovery to around 3.5 percent in 1999 and averaging
over 5 percent thereafter," said the memorandum which is published
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into account recent developments, our main priority at
this juncture is to sustain economic growth, limit the adverse
effects of the crisis and provide for an early, strong, and
lasting recovery," it said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum said the government has formulated policies to
prevent a slide of the economy into recession including keeping
the budget deficit at a manageable level while limiting the
inflation rate to 8 percent next year and 5 to 6 percent in the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
This year, the country's inflation rate is expected to hit an
average 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
To improve the fiscal position, the government is also
committed to imposing a tax on land conversion, tax on idle land,
road users tax, increase in registration fees for luxury cars and
3-percent tariff on imports of capital equipment for firms located
in special economic zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
