<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia May Lift Import Duty on Auto Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
reportedly considering lifting both the import duty and
value-added tax (VAT) on automotive parts in a bid to salvage the
crippled automotive industry and the transportation sector.
</P>
<P>
The government is currently studying the possibility of
slashing the 25-percent import duty and 10-percent VAT on car
spare parts to lower their skyrocketing domestic prices, Minister
of Industry and Trade Rahardi Ramelan was quoted Wednesday by the
Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Officials of our ministry and the Finance Ministry are
currently in discussions to finalize the removal of the two taxes
soon," Rahardi said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah's 75-percent drop against the U.S. dollar since
August last year has pushed up prices of spare parts drastically,
debilitating all 300,000 public transportation companies across
the country.
</P>
<P>
Only 331,000 of the country's 2.4 million public transportation
vehicles are still road-worthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spare parts which are particularly in high demand in the
country include tires, batteries, oil filters, air filters, fuel
filters, fuses, brake pads, clutches, clutch covers, timing belts,
fan belts, distributor contacts, tire bearing and light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
The Land Public Transports Organization said spare parts
contributed 44.74 percent of its members' operation costs if the
rupiah was 10,000 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has gradually strengthened to about 11,000 to the
greenback recently after it bottomed out at about 17,000 earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of public transportation drivers held a massive
strike in Medan, capital of North Sumatra province, on September
14 to demand the lowering of prices of automotive spare parts. The
strike led to a vandalism and looting spree.
</P>
<P>
In Banjarmasin, capital of South Kalimantan province, a strike
by thousands of public vehicle drivers entered its second day on
Tuesday, causing difficulties to thousands of commuters, including
school children. The strikers are demanding a reduction in the
prices of vehicle spare parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
