<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimes in Indonesian Capital Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,600 crimes have
occurred in Jakarta over the last three months, the Indonesian
Observer Wednesday quoted city police officers as saying.
</P>
<P>
That is an increase of almost 4 percent over the same period of
the previous year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In Central Jakarta alone, from the beginning of the year up
until August, almost 1,000 crimes were committed in this area,
ranging from fraud to motorcycle theft.
</P>
<P>
According to Central Jakarta Deputy Police Chief Major Ronny
Sompie, there have been 450 car and motorcycle thefts, of which
350 involved murder. All of the stolen motor vehicles ended up in
South Sumatra province or the provinces of Java.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta Police Chief Major General Noegroho Djajoesman
acknowledged that robberies have increased greatly this year.
</P>
<P>
He predicts violent crime will go up as many bandits are
joining forces and committing robberies in groups. Most of those
arrested had turned to crime as a result of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Most of Jakarta's criminals frequently failed to obtain
legitimate work due to a lack of skills or qualifications,
Noegroho added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
