<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vegetable "King" in China's Desert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Gao Zhendong, a farmer in Yulin
city in northwest China's Shaanxi Province never imagined that
growing vegetables in the desert could bring him a fortune.
</P>
<P>
Since early last year, his 18-member Desert Vegetables Company
has produced more than 1.8 million kg of vegetables, bringing a
net income of over 800,000 yuan (96,700 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Stalwart and with dark skin, 37-year-old Gao said the over
1,300 hectares of sandy land he leased could " well keep me
busy all my life".
</P>
<P>
Born in a village in Yulin's Mizhi County, Gao left home to go
into business after graduating from senior high school. But a trip
to Israel kindled his desire to grow vegetables in desert.
</P>
<P>
That was in May 1996, when he went to Israel to investigate a
possible agricultural investment project. During his 20-day tour,
he was amazed by Israel's highly efficient agriculture in a land
severely short of water resources.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis irrigate vegetables just like feeding babies,"
he said, " every drop of water is used scientifically."
</P>
<P>
If Israel can export vegetables," why can't I turn the desert
in Yulin into a vegetable basket," Gao returned home with this
idea in mind.
</P>
<P>
He then shuttled between China's elite universities and
agricultural research institutes, and invited 20 experts to become
his personal advisers. When told that his plan was workable, he
resolutely went ahead to put it into practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
