<HEADLINE> Vegetable "King" in China's Desert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But his wife thought he must be crazy and wouldn't agree to
investing in desert. " You are burying our hard-earned savings in
sand," she said, " what will our two children and I live on in the
future?"
</P>
<P>
Gao insisted, and at last managed to get the money from his
wife.
</P>
<P>
He bought 13.2 hectares of desert land near a Yulin village
called Liuputan and set up his Desert Vegetables Company, which
grows vegetables in plastic greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
Half a year later, when he put the first sum of money he earned
into his wife's hands, she gave it back and then followed him out
to the desert.
</P>
<P>
Gao said it is not so difficult to grow vegetables in the
desert so long as scientific methods are used. He first bulldozed
the sand dunes, dug wells and then built greenhouses designed by
experts.
</P>
<P>
"I grow vegetables with high-tech methods," he said proudly, and
indeed he is the first person to introduce Israel's drip-irrigation
technique and vegetables into the Yulin desert.
</P>
<P>
In the 87 plastic greenhouses, more than 20 species of
vegetables are grown, including cherry tomatoes, bell peppers and
eggplants from Israel and balsam pears from south China.
</P>
