<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuggets Names D'Antoni as Head Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Denver Nuggets named on
Tuesday Mike D'Antoni as its head coach after one of the worst
seasons in the club's franchise.
</P>
<P>
Thus, D'Antoni, who joined Nuggets as director of player
personnel last year, becomes the club's seventh coach this decade
by replacing Bill Hanzlik who was fired after an 11-71 season.
</P>
<P>
With seven seasons in the Italian League, D'Antoni, who
briefly served as interim general manager last season, was hired
by general manager Dan Issel who took over the team in March.
</P>
<P>
Before joining Nuggets, D'Antoni compiled a 144-68 coaching
record with Benetton of the Italian League. His teams made the
playoffs each season, and Benetton won the 1997 Italian League
Championship.
</P>
<P>
D'Antoni, 47, also had success as a player, helping Milan to
five league championships, two European Cup titles and two
Intercontinental Cups in 13 seasons. He spent four years in the
NBA and one in the American Basketball Association, a former
rival to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
D'Antoni served as e Nuggets' interim general manager after
Allan Bristow was fired in February. Issel took over the team in
March, and D'Antoni finished the season as an assistant to
Hanzlik.
</P>
<P>
As interim general manager, his most notablove was signing
point guard Cory Alexander, who played a pivotal role in helping
the Nuggets avoid the worst record in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
They avoided that dubious distinction by winning six of their
final 19 games to finih two games better than the 9-73 record set
by the 1972-73 Philadelphia 76ers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
