<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight FMs to Introduce Nuclear Draft Resolution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ministers of
Foreign Affairs of Brazil, Egypt, Ireland, Mexico, New Zealand,
Slovenia, South Africa and Sweden on Tuesday issued a communique,
reaffirming their intention to introduce at the current session of
the General Assembly a draft resolution on establishing
Nuclear-weapon-free world.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution is entitled "Towards a Nuclear-Weapon-Free
World: The need for a New Agenda."
</P>
<P>
The eight ministers, who are all here to attend the 53rd
session of the General Assembly, met in New York this afternoon to
assess the developments in the field of nuclear disarmament and
non-proliferation following the issue of the Joint Declaration
"Towards a Nuclear-Weapon-Free World" in June 9, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed the firm hope that this resolution,
which reflects the repeated calls of the international community
for urgent action on the important issue of nuclear program,
will receive overwhelming support from the Member States of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The ministers invited all other States to join them in the
efforts to achieve a world free from nuclear weapons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
