<HEADLINE> Boothe Denies Flo-Jo Drug Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- British athletics coach Lorna
Boothe denied claiming on Tuesday that Florence Griffith-Joyner,
who died from a suspected heart seizure on Monday, had taken
drugs.
</P>
<P>
Booth was quoted in newspaper reports as saying she had met a
nurse in a California hospital in 1987-88 who was adamant
Griffith-Joyner had been administered performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
But in a statement to PA Sport, Boothe said: "I am saddened to
hear of the death of Florence Griffith-Joyner - she was a young
woman and most importantly perhaps, a young mother. Contrary to
some press reports I have never trained with Florence
Griffith-Joyner nor have I claimed that she took drugs."
</P>
<P>
She continued: "I did live in Los Angeles between 1984 and
1991 when I was working in banking but I have no evidence to
suggest that she used performance-enhancing drugs or illegal
substances.
</P>
<P>
"There were rumours surrounding her outstanding success but it
is unwise and inappropriate for me or indeed anyone to
speculate," she added. 
</P>
