<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> English Soccer League to Launch Pay-per-view </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The first pay-per-view
experiment in English football is set to start early in the New
Year following a ground-breaking announcement by the Football
League on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of six or seven matches between Christmas and the end
of the season will be chosen as the guinea pigs for a live
experiment which could go some way to determine the future of the
game's television coverage.
</P>
<P>
The matches will be shown, for a cost to the viewer of between
5 and 10 pounds each, on a variety of days and times in addition
to the current Nationwide League games already shown on Sky
Sports on Friday evenings and Sunday lunch-times.
</P>
<P>
They should feature a cross-section of teams, although bigger
clubs such as Sunderland and Manchester City, local derbies and
table-topping clashes are expected to dominate.
</P>
<P>
No deal has yet been finalised, although BSkyB is the
favourites to win the broadcasting rights, and the profits are
set to be split between the two competing clubs in each fixture
as well as the rest of the Nationwide League teams.
</P>
<P>
The Football League board put forward the plan to gather
evidence about the market for pay-per-view ahead of the
renegotiation of the existing TV deals in the next two years,
when they hope to resurrect a joint contract with the Premier
League.
</P>
<P>
The idea is by no means revolutionary yet the impact on
football may well be.
</P>
<P>
Many of the biggest fights in the boxing world are already
only available on pay-per-view, while Manchester United and other
leading clubs would be assured of sizeable audiences if the
Premier League gave the go-ahead to BSkyB or set up on their own.
</P>
<P>
If it is proved that viewers are also prepared to pay extra to
watch chosen Nationwide League games, then - like it or not
-pay-per-view could well become enshrined as part of the national
culture in Britain, as it is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Apart from worries over saturation coverage and cost, there
remains one other huge obstacle to overcome - a hearing in the
Restrictive Practices Court in January which the League admit
could "torpedo" all of their potentially lucrative plans.
</P>
<P>
If the court agree with the Office of Fair Trading that clubs
should be allowed to negotiate TV deals individually - and not
through the Football League or Premier League - then the game is
set for a monumental shake-up.
</P>
<P>
Football League chairman, David Sheepshanks, told BBC: "Any
experiment must be on the basis that it is for the benefit of
all, not just the clubs which are featured.
</P>
<P>
"It must also be seen as something additional, we must
ring-fence the current TV diet of our supporters.
</P>
<P>
"Will it lead to saturation coverage? Well, no one is forcing
people to pay for this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0285 </DOCNO>
