<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Treasury Reports First Federal Surplus in 29 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
likely to record its first federal budget surplus in 29 years as
the 1998 fiscal year is approaching to the end, the Treasury
Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The department reported a deficit of 11.2 billion U.S. dollars
in August, down 68 percent from a year ago. That put the surplus
for the first 11 months of the budget year at 31.8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
With quarterly tax payments flowing into federal coffers in
September, the surplus for the full year should easily double that
amount and surpass the latest government projections. The
September surplus last year was 49.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, the Congressional Budget Office projected a 63
billion dollars surplus for fiscal 1998, which ends September 30.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit hit a record 290 billion dollars in 1992 and
declined to a 23-year low of 22 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spending for fiscal 1998 through August totaled 1.51 trillion
dollars, up 2.2 percent, or not much more than the inflation rate.
However, revenue, at 1.54 trillion dollars, is up 9.7 percent from
the same period during the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In August, receipts totaled 111.7 billion dollars, up 8 percent
from August 1997, and spending totaled 122.9 billion dollars, down
11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
As usual, the largest spending categories for the month were:
Social Security, 31.7 billion dollars; Department of Health and
Human Services programs including Medicare and Medicaid, 25.4
billion dollars; interest on the 5.42 trillion dollar national
debt, 24 billion dollars; and the military spending, 17.4 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
