<HEADLINE> UK Troops in N. Ireland to be Withdrawn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Up to UK 400 troops are to be
withdrawn from Northern Ireland in the next two weeks as a result
of the improving security situation, a senior police official said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland police chief Ronnie Flanagan said in
Belfast that the members of 39 Regiment (Royal Artillery) and the
1st Battalion the Highlanders will return to their bases in
mainland over the next two weeks, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, routine army patrolling will be ended in the south
Londonderry area from this weekend, he added. Military patrolling
in Belfast, the provincial capital, ended 10 days ago as security
threat has been considerably reduced.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan said the troop reductions were being made as a result
of the continual review of the security situation in which he and
the army have worked closely together.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased the "improving security situation"
enabled him to operate more widely across the province with a
reduced military presence.  
</P>
