<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Rally but Close off Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- European share prices rallied
on Tuesday from steep losses suffered during the previous session.
However, analysts were braced for further volatile times ahead.
</P>
<P>
London shares have held onto strong gains to close well up
despite Wall Street lurching into the red and eroding some of the
advance.
</P>
<P>
The leading FTSE 100 index ended the session with a gain of 113
points at 5103, having peaked at 5124 just ahead of New York's
opening.
</P>
<P>
Markets everywhere showed relief at indications that U.S.
President Bill Clinton will weather Republican moves to impeach
him, as his approval ratings even climbed after yesterday's
televised videotape testimony to the Congressional Grand Jury.
</P>
<P>
Even Tokyo managed gains overnight, despite signs that a
hoped-for agreement on banking reform was crumbling.
</P>
<P>
But uncertainty reigns. Market players remain worried about the
outlook for Latin American markets, particularly about how
regional collapses could prove dangerous for the US.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there has been a dearth of domestic and
international data ahead of Thursday's second quarter GDP
revisions for both the UK and the US.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, share prices rallied by a strong 3.19 percent as
the Dax 30 index, which had fallen by 3.58 percent on Monday,
finished at 4,575.15 points. The market was boosted, too, by
firmer markets in Asia and by the reaction to President Bill
Clinton's televised grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
But traders said the gains did not signal a change in the
market's mood as concerns about Asia and Russia still continued.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, share prices closed well below the day's highs,
paring early gains as a result of continued uncertainty and
volatility in global markets. The Cac 40 index finished just 5.33
points higher at 3,347.98.
</P>
<P>
Opening gains on Wall Street had little effect on the French
market, but as the Dow Jones began to lose ground the Cac 40
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
One dealer said: "Today I don't think Wall Street's gains
helped us very much. Yesterday they were much more significant.
But when it went down, we followed it."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
