<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Vice-President Calls for Eliminating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-President
Christon Tembo Tuesday called on African countries to make
greater efforts to prevent more people from descending into
abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech at the Southern Africa Region
Microcredit Summit here, Tembo said, "We do not have to be told
by any one from out of the continent that unless we do something
about poverty, we are going to be the only continent that enters
the new millennium with decreasing standards of living and also
decreasing life expectancy."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to let this happen," the Zambian
vice-president said, calling for a great effort to prevent more
people from descending into abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
The problem of poverty is one that no country in the African
continent can afford to take lightly, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tembo said when the current Zambian government took power
early 1990s it adopted a market economy and the choice to change
course has and continues to be a painful one.
</P>
<P>
In the process of restructuring the economy, there are many
casualties, he said, a government has to have a strong nerve to
remain on the course especially when it sees the resultant
suffering of its people.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government strongly believes that the
liberalization of the economy will encourage Zambians to work
harder for themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tembo said that because of the extent of breakdown the economy
had suffered, its rejuvenation will take a long time and Zambian
people will not be patient for ever with the real live problem of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said the summit gives both the governments of southern
Africa and the microcredit practitioners an opportunity to
work together.
</P>
<P>
But the Zambian vice-president said that in terms of giving
loans, the experience in his country has not been good at all
because over the years people believe that services by government
or money belonging to government need not be paid back as they
belong to the people.
</P>
<P>
Tembo therefore urged the microcredit practitioners to build
into their programs checks and balances that win people from this
dependence, thereby re-orienting their outlook in the proper use
of credit and the obligations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
