<HEADLINE> Top Palestinian Peace Negotiator Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Top Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat has resigned because of differences with other
Palestinian officials on the handling of the Israeli-Palestinian
talks, Israel Radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Erekat submitted a letter to Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat Monday, asking Arafat to remove him
from his post as the chief Palestinian negotiator, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat has not responded to his resignation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Erekat was angry that he was sidestepped
in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. He had held talks with
the Israelis on behalf of the PNA since the two sides resumed
direct negotiations in July, but was replaced by Palestinian
Legislator Council Speaker Ahmed Queria (Abu Ala) in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Erekat is also minister of local government in the PNA and he
did not resign from that post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
