<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were
killed and three others wounded in south Lebanon Tuesday by a
Lebanese guerrillas' roadside bomb, the official National News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The remote-controlled bomb exploded when a patrol of Israeli
soldiers passed by the village of Dir Sarayan on the edge of the
Israeli occupied security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack, saying one of its guerrilla units
detonated the bomb.
</P>
<P>
But, Israeli army said in a statement that the soldiers were
killed and wounded when the tank they were riding turned over at
the village, calling it an "accident."
</P>
<P>
The agency said following the incident that Israeli helicopters
arrived at the site and took the casualties to the Israeli
territory.
</P>
<P>
The fresh attack has brought to 14 the number of Israeli
soldiers killed in south Lebanon so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 to protect its north from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been engaged in a war of attrition trying to oust
Israeli troops and their proxy militia South Lebanon Army out of
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
