<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Weakens Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, Sept 22 (Reuters) - The Kenyan Shilling weakened
against the U.S. Dollar in trading Tuesday after a bout of
corporate demand for the greenback, currency dealers said.
</P>
<P>
They said there was some activity from corporates seeking to
purchase U.S. Dollars when the markets opened at 9.00 a.m. (0600
GMT), which drove the Shilling lower against the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
One commercial bank moved from its opening rate of 60.30 to
60.50 while another opened at 60.10/20 and quickly eased to
60.10/40, according to a press report here.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the sudden flurry of demand for the Dollar
fizzled out quickly and that demand was not high enough to move
the market drastically, in view of high Dollar inflows from the
tea sector.
</P>
<P>
"Demand is not high enough to make the Shilling weaken any
further," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
"Margins have widened a little. But there is tea money coming
in to meet current demand," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Citibank said in a market report that importers' demand for
foreign exchange was down this year by approximately 20 percent
compared to last year -- "a true indication of the slowdown in
Kenya's economy."
</P>
<P>
Citibank said limited foreign currency flows showed the
effects of a failing economy on the currency market.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan economy is in decline, with gross domestic product
(GDP) growth forecast to fall to 1.6 percent in 1998 compared to
2.3 percent last year, according to the Central Bank of Kenya
data.
</P>
<P>
The central bank posted the Shilling at a mean indicative rate
of 60.1000 against the greenback compared to 60.0678 on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
