<DOCNO> XIE19980923.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Encourages Japan to Speed up Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday encouraged Japan to speed up financial reforms and help
restore economic recovery in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the United States wanted to help Tokyo find a
way out of its problems but he avoided any public comments
pressing Japan to accept specific policies.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is virtually unanimous support in the world for
the kind of financial reforms that would restore economic growth
in Japan," Clinton said during a picture-taking session with
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held what Obuchi described as "very candid
talks" earlier in the day on spreading Asian financial and
economic crisis as well as on Japan's efforts to deal with its own
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the talks, White House spokesman Mike McCurry told
reporters:"We obviously have our concerns about the reforms we
believe are necessary in the Japanese banking system and its
financial system generally."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "both sides understand the importance of
moving swiftly."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President's message to Obuchi was that it would be in
the interests of the people of Japan" to institute reforms to help
the recovery of Japan and be a role model for all of Asia, McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the talks, Obuchi acknowledged that
the steps Japan ultimately takes will have "very large
implications worldwide."
</P>
<P>
"I intend to make my very best effort at addressing this
issue," he said. "I am convinced that we will be able to do
something."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told reporters
after the meeting that Obuchi told Clinton his government planned
to implement measures to restart economic growth quickly.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Obuchi made it clear that it was his intention
to take appropriate measures to secure an early turnaround in the
Japanese economy," Summers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
