<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Potassium Diet May Protect Against Stroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Diets rich in fruits,
vegetables and whole grain cereals may reduce a person's risk of
stroke, especially in individuals with high blood pressure,
according to a study in the latest issue of Circulation, Journal
of the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
"This beneficial effect appears to be due to the high potassium
content of these diets, but other components of fruits and
vegetables may also contribute to the reduced risk of stroke,"
said Dr. Alberto Ascherio, associate professor of nutrition and
epidemiology at Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
In a study of 44000 men, researchers found that those whos'
diets with high potassium had a 38 percent lower risk of stroke
than those whos' diets with lowest potassium.
</P>
<P>
Ascherio said there is strong support for a stroke-preventive
effect from diets rich in potassium, magnesium and cereal fiber.
This was found to be particularly true in individuals with high
blood pressure, but further study in a bigger scale is still
needed to prove their finding.
</P>
<P>
Sources of dietary potassium include tomatoes, spinach,
bananas, oranges and other fruits and vegetables. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
