<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Leaves for U.N. General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar left Abuja Tuesday for the United States via
London to the attend the United Nations General Assembly in New
York, the Nigerian TV Authority (NTA) said.
</P>
<P>
While in London, Abubakar met with the British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and he will also address a news conference Wednesday
before leaving for New York.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader will address the U.N. General Assembly
Thursday afternoon, which will be broadcast home live, NTA said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar is also expected to meet with U.S. President Bill
Clinton. The U.S. president has said that he is eager to meet
with the new Nigerian leader.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader will leave New York for home Sunday via
France where he will meet with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's three-nation tour marks the climax of Nigeria's
return to the international society after years of sanctions by
the West during the reign of late leader General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The new warm-up has been made possible by Abubakar's series of
new policies toward national reconciliation and democratization,
including the release of all political detainees and a new
transition to civil rule program that will usher in an elected
civilian government by the end of May 1999.  
</P>
