<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho King Not Informed of Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Head of State,
King Letsie III, was kept in the dark about South Africa's military
intervention in his country, South African television reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) quoted King Letsie's
younger brother as saying that neither the king nor any other members of
the royal family had been informed of the foreign intervention in the
Lesotho crisis, either by South African or Lesotho government.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa had a lot to answer for and the invasion had
soured bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties also released a statement, saying the
king was not informed of the South African operation.
</P>
<P>
South African Democratic Party Leader, Tony Leon, confirmed that the
Lesotho monarchy was not givem knowledge of the military operation
before hand.
</P>
<P>
He said the royal family only heard of the invasion when one of its
members went to the border at about 4.30 a.m. (0230 GMT) in response
to rumors that an invasion was imminent.
</P>
<P>
Leon said he was contacted by the royal family and was advised that
the royal family believed the military intervention was "precipitate
and counter-productive since peaceful means to restore order to
Lesotho had not been exhausted."
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili earlier Tuesday accused
King Letsie of siding with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili said he was unable to consult the king about a request for
foreign military intervention because the king was part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
He said the king harbored opposition supporters in his palace for
seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
About 600 South African soldiers entered Lesotho early Tuesday
morning to help restore peace in the capital of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 Botswanan troops arrived in Ladybrand near Lesotho-South
African border Tuesday afternoon and were expected to join South
African soldiers Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
South African troops encountered fierce resistance from Lesotho
mutinous soldiers and civilians and there were unconfirmed reports
that 30 people had been killed in skirmishes. Among the dead were five
South African soldiers and 17 Lesotho soldiers.
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswanan soldiers were dispatched as Southern
African Development Community peacekeepers at the request of the
Lesotho government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
