<HEADLINE> Gunfire, Looting Continue in Lesotho's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Shooting and looting
are continuing into Tuesday night in the center of Lesotho
capital Maseru, South African television reported.
</P>
<P>
Gunshot were heard in some sections of the city, which is
situated near the South African border. There was no soldiers
and police in sight, unidentified witnesses were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Many shops, mainly South African-owned ones, have been looted
by hundreds of people, the witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The streets of Maseru have become littered with glass from
broken shop windows, and youths who earlier went on the rampage
through the city streets were setting around drinking.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said many Lesotho people had expressed strong
anti-South African sentiments.
</P>
<P>
"People are upset about the decision to send troops here,"
said a Lesotho youth, who asked not to be identified. He blamed
South Africa for chaos that erupted after South African troops
entered Lesotho in the early hours of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"On Tuesday morning we were woken by choppers and army
vehicles with troops who shot some of our soldiers, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Acting South African President Mangosuthu Buthelezi defended
that South Africa and Botswana's military intervention in Lesotho
was to help restore stability and to find a lasting political
solution to the crisis in the tiny mountainous country.
</P>
<P>
The current military intervention was not that of South Africa
but an operation of the Southern African Development Community,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said that a 200-strong Botswanan peacekeeping
troops are due to cross into Lesotho to join their 600 South
African counterparts Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association earlier quoted an unnamed
South African government officia as saying that Zimbabwe had
also joined the intervention.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no detailed report about Zimbabwe's
participation in the operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
