<HEADLINE> Mandela Says He Supports Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela pledged support for U.S. President Bill Clinton
even if everybody else deserts him hours before the two leaders
meet here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon at the South African Embassy, Mandela
said he extends the support because no other American president
has identified himself more with the aspirations of black people.
</P>
<P>
"He has my full support in everything that he does," Mandela
said. "In the jurisprudence of many... civilized countries, a
person is regarded as innocent until he's convicted."
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he refrains from interfering in domestic affairs
of other countries, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "I want to tell you that although I do not know
the history of the United States very well, in my view there is no
(prior) president who has identified himself with the aspirations
of blacks inside this country and in Africa."
</P>
<P>
"I will support my friends even if they have been deserted by
the entire group," added Mandela. "I will support him."
</P>
<P>
Mandela also decried the "grave injustice" of Western countries
judging South Africa by their standards.
</P>
<P>
"We have parents who have never seen the inside of a school,
who cannot write their names," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who served 27 years in prisons before his relase in
1990, admitted the new black-run government has made mistakes
since South Africa rid itself of the white supremacist apartheid
system in 1994.
</P>
<P>
But he said the missteps were partly due to inexperience of the
rulers and the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
"Suddenly, without any previous training, they are called upon
to run a developed country with modern ports and harbors, with
modern communications,... with a sophisticated banking and
financial system," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
"For you to judge us on the basis of what happens in America,
in Canada and in Europe is a grave injustice," added Mandela.
</P>
<P>
"Judge us from the background from which we come.... We came
from years in prison, from the bush, from exile and from the
underground," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela asked for U.S. investment and help in rebuilding the
society and economy of his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
