<HEADLINE> Public Remains Supportive of Clinton Despite Video  Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Two-thirds of Americans
surveyed after the airing of President Bill Clinton's grand jury
testimony say he was evasive in his answers and even more don't
buy his narrow definition of sexual relations, but most people
don't want him removed from office either, polls show.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's job approval rating still ranges from 60 percent to
66 percent, according to surveys taken Monday night by ABC News,
CNN/USA Today/Gallup and NBC News. About six out of 10 oppose his
resignation or impeachment, said the polls taken hours after the
videotape was shown nationally.
</P>
<P>
While most say Clinton should not be removed from office, 68
percent in the Gallup poll said the Lewinsky matter is causing
significant harm to the country.
</P>
<P>
Six out of 10 said Congress was wrong to release the videotape
and prosecutors were wrong to ask about such intimate details. And
the president was right not to answer such questions, according to
70 percent of those in the ABC survey.
</P>
<P>
Among those who saw the videotape, 45 percent approved of the
president's handling of the testimony and 41 percent disapproved,
the ABC poll said.
</P>
<P>
"The overnight polling data suggest that the American people
now have a more sympathetic view of the president than they had
before," said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
But 68 percent of those who saw the videotape described
Clinton's answers as evasive and four out of five disagreed with
Clinton's narrow legal definition of "sexual relations."
</P>
<P>
The percentage who think the president should be impeached and
removed from office, 41 percent, has not grown significantly in
the last week but has increased by 11 points in the ABC poll since
September 13, just after the report from Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr was released.
</P>
<P>
However, Henry Hyde, a Republican and chairmen of the Judiciary
Committee of the House of Representatives, said, "Poll-taking is
an art and not a science."
</P>
<P>
Such reactions are understandable, pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
"People want there to be more reaction. There's frustration,"
said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center. "It's sort
of a 'shoot the messenger' reaction. There's been a consensus
within the polls on this that gives them legitimacy. But people
should stay tuned."
</P>
<P>
The CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll of 631 adults had a margin of
error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. The ABC poll of 523
adults and the NBC poll of 508 adults had margins of error of plus
or minus 4.5 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
