<HEADLINE> Singapore Leader Urges U.S. to Lower Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Singapore's Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong said on Tuesday the United States should
consider cutting interest rates to help the Asia's economy to
grow.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce here, Goh said the
outlook for Asian economies was bleak.
</P>
<P>
"What are the prospects for the Asian economies? There is no
doubt that the short-term economic prospects for the region are
bleak," he said, adding, it still remained to be seen whether the
crisis would worsen substantially and how long it would take to
recover.
</P>
<P>
He said much would depend on the steps taken by Asian
governments themselves but he also added that the United States
could play an important role. He asked the United States to
support the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
"As the world's only economic superpower, the U.S. must take
the lead in mobilizing international support to tackle the Asian
crisis," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
Asked during the forum whether a U.S. interest rate cut was
also needed, Goh said it would help make the Japanese yen more
fairly valued versus the dollar and would thus help the rest of
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"It is an option that the U.S. ought to look at to stabilize
the situation in the world," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that a rate cut by the Group of Seven rich
nations would be less likely because of reluctance on the part of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Goh urged the U.S. and Europe to resist the temptation to try
to isolate themselves from the world turmoil by closing their
markets, saying they would miss out once Asia did recover.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Singapore's economy, Goh said he expected a
minimal amount of growth next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
