<HEADLINE> U.S. Sells Jet Fighters Worth $2.5 Billion to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States
announced on Tuesday that it would sell a package of 30 advanced
F-15 fighter jets to Israel for 2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Pentagon stressed that the "I" models of
the F-15 jets would help maintain Israel's military edge over its
neighbors
</P>
<P>
The attack jets would be equipped with sophisticated electronic
targeting pods and increase the Israeli Air Force's ground-attack
capabilities, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The F-15I jets would be equipped with AN/APG-70 or AN/APG-63
radars and "LANTIRN" navigation and targeting pods used to enhance
ground-attack capabilities, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Israel already has F-15s in its inventory, but the "I" models
would represent a major step forward in both air-to-air and
ground-attack capability for the United States' closest ally in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the Pentagon announced last Wednesday that it
had offered two billion U.S. dollars in sophisticated AMRAAM and
other aircraft military missiles made by Raytheon Co. to the
United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., who has urged other countries not to sell weapons to
the Middle East, is the biggest salesman of weapons in the region.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the sale to Israel may be resulted from the
progress in the Palestine-Israel talks. The U.S. is trying to
persuade Israel to compromise in the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
